<deck>
  <title>AP CSA Essential Knowledge</title>

  <section>
    <title>Data types</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A type is a set of values (a domain) and a set of operations on them.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two things define a type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A set of values (a domain) and a set of operations on them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In the definition of a type, what is the "domain"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The set of values that belong to that type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>int</code> considered a different type from <code>double</code>, even though both represent numbers?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They have different domains (sets of possible values) and different operations defined on them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone says "a type is just a set of values," what part of the definition are they missing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The set of operations defined on those values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to say that operations are part of a type's definition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A type is not just its values but also what you can do with them; the allowed operations are integral to what the type is.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Data types in Java are either primitive or reference types.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two broad categories of data types in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitive types and reference types.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is every Java data type either primitive or reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, every Java data type falls into one of these two categories.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a type isn't primitive in Java, what must it be?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java distinguish primitive types from reference types?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because they are stored and passed around differently: primitive values are held directly, while reference values are references to objects elsewhere in memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Given a new Java type you've never seen, how would you classify it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Check whether it's one of the built-in primitives (like <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>boolean</code>); if not, it's a reference type.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The primitive data types used in this course, which represent numbers and logical values, are `int`, `double`, and `boolean`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which three primitive types are used in AP CSA?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which primitive type represents whole numbers?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which primitive type represents numbers with fractional parts?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which primitive type represents logical (true/false) values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do the primitive types <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code> collectively represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Numbers (whole and fractional) and logical values.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The main reference types we use are `String`, arrays, `ArrayList` and other classes that we write ourselves all of which extend `Object`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name the main reference types used in AP CSA.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>, arrays, <code>ArrayList</code>, and classes we write ourselves.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What class do all the reference types we use ultimately extend?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>String</code> a primitive or reference type in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>ArrayList</code> and our own classes extend <code>Object</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They inherit from <code>Object</code>, so they automatically get the methods defined on <code>Object</code> and can be treated as <code>Object</code> values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are <code>String</code> and an array similar in terms of Java's type system?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are reference types whose values are references to data stored elsewhere in memory, and both ultimately extend <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The primitive data types and `String`s each have a syntax for writing literal values in Java programs, e.g. `1234`, `9.876`, `true`, and `"foobar"`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "literal" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A piece of syntax that directly represents a value in source code, such as <code>1234</code> or <code>"foobar"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which types have literal syntax in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The primitive types and <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an <code>int</code> literal and a <code>double</code> literal.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>1234</code> is an <code>int</code> literal; <code>9.876</code> is a <code>double</code> literal.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the difference between the literals <code>true</code> and <code>"true"</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> is a <code>boolean</code> literal; <code>"true"</code> is a <code>String</code> literal containing four characters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you write a literal value for an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, <code>ArrayList</code> has no literal syntax; you must construct one. Only primitives and <code>String</code> have literal syntax.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Integer values in Java are represented by the data type `int`. `int`s are stored using four bytes (32 bits) of memory. Therefore, an `int` value must be in the range from `Integer.MIN_VALUE` to `Integer.MAX_ VALUE` inclusive.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How many bytes (and bits) of memory does an <code>int</code> occupy in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Four bytes, or 32 bits.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the range of valid <code>int</code> values in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the range of <code>int</code> bounded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because an <code>int</code> is stored in only 32 bits of memory, there are finitely many values it can represent.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which Java type represents integer values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>int</code> and <code>double</code>: which one has a limited range, and why?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both have limits because both use a fixed number of bits, but <code>int</code> in particular is capped by its 32-bit range between <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> and <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>If an `int` expression would evaluate to a numeric value outside of the possible range for `int`, an overflow occur resulting in a mathematically incorrect `int` value. (For instance `Integer.MAX_VALUE + 1` evaluates to `Integer.MIN_VALUE`.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is integer overflow in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When an <code>int</code> expression produces a value outside the legal <code>int</code> range, it wraps around to a mathematically incorrect <code>int</code> value instead of raising an error.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE + 1</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when an <code>int</code> computation exceeds <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It overflows, producing an incorrect <code>int</code> value rather than throwing an exception.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does Java throw an exception on <code>int</code> overflow?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the expression silently evaluates to a wrong <code>int</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Your program multiplies two large <code>int</code>s and gets a negative result. What likely happened?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The mathematically correct result overflowed the <code>int</code> range and wrapped around, producing an incorrect (possibly negative) value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Numbers with fractional parts are represented by the data type `double`. A `double` is stored in a 64-bit representation that encodes a significand, and exponent, and a sign, similar to the way scientific notation works.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which Java type represents numbers with fractional parts?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many bits does a <code>double</code> occupy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>64 bits.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What three parts encode a <code>double</code>'s value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A significand, an exponent, and a sign.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>A <code>double</code>'s representation is similar to what mathematical notation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scientific notation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> store their values.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> uses 32 bits as a plain two's complement integer; <code>double</code> uses 64 bits split into a sign, an exponent, and a significand, like scientific notation.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Logical values (true and false) are represented by the `boolean` data type. There are only two `boolean` values: written as `true` and `false`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which Java type represents logical values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many distinct <code>boolean</code> values exist in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Exactly two: <code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are the two <code>boolean</code> values written as literals?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>"true"</code> a valid <code>boolean</code> value in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; <code>"true"</code> is a <code>String</code> literal. The <code>boolean</code> literal is just <code>true</code>, with no quotes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>boolean</code> a useful type to have built into the language?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because logical true/false values are fundamental to control flow (like <code>if</code> and <code>while</code> conditions), so the language gives them a dedicated type with exactly two values.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All the other data types we will use are reference data types which means the values that are stored in variables and passed to and returned from methods are references to where the real value lives in memory.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "reference" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A value that points to where an object actually lives in memory, rather than containing the object itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you assign a reference-type value to a variable, what is actually stored in the variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the object's location in memory, not the object itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What gets passed to a method when its parameter is a reference type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the object, so the method can access the same object in memory that the caller has.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does storing a reference-type value differ from storing a primitive value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A primitive variable directly holds the value; a reference variable holds a reference pointing to where the real value lives in memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two variables hold references to the same object, what happens when one modifies the object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both variables see the change, because they refer to the same underlying object in memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`null` is a special reference value that represents "no object". It can be written as a literal value as `null`. It is the default value for uninitialized member variables and the unitialized elements of arrays of reference types such as `String[]`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>null</code> represent in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A special reference value meaning "no object."</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you write <code>null</code> as a literal in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just as <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of an uninitialized reference-type member variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>null</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What values do the elements of a newly created <code>String[]</code> contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>null</code>, since the elements of an array of a reference type default to <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>null</code> a primitive value or a reference value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference value: a special one that refers to no object.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Using the dot operator to call a method or access an instance variable on a `null` value causes a `NullPointerException` to be thrown.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you call a method on a <code>null</code> value?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which operator triggers a <code>NullPointerException</code> when used on <code>null</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The dot operator (<code>.</code>), when used to call a method or access an instance variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>null.length()</code> fail?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>null</code> refers to no object, so there's nothing for the dot operator to call a method on; Java throws a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You get a <code>NullPointerException</code> on a line like <code>s.foo()</code>. What does that tell you about <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>s</code> was <code>null</code> at that moment, so the dot operator had no object to act on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does accessing an instance variable via the dot operator on <code>null</code> also throw a <code>NullPointerException</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; any use of the dot operator on a <code>null</code> reference, whether for a method call or field access, throws a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Variables</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each variable has associated memory that is used to hold its value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does every variable have associated with it to hold its value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where is a variable's value actually stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In memory associated with that variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you declare <code>int x = 5;</code>, what happens behind the scenes with memory?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Memory is set aside for <code>x</code>, and the value <code>5</code> is stored there.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a variable exist without any memory backing it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Every variable has memory associated with it to hold its value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the relationship between a variable and memory?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable is a name for a piece of memory that holds its value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The memory associated with a variable of a primitive type holds the actual representation of the primitive value while the memory associated with a variable holding a reference type holds a reference to the actual data which exists somewhere else in the computer's memory.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the memory of a primitive-type variable hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The actual representation of the primitive value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the memory of a reference-type variable hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the actual data, which lives elsewhere in memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do primitive and reference variables differ in what their memory stores?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitive variables store the value itself; reference variables store a reference (pointer) to data stored elsewhere.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you write <code>int a = 42;</code>, where does the number <code>42</code> live?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Directly in the memory for <code>a</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you write <code>String s = "hi";</code>, what exactly is stored in the memory for <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to a <code>String</code> object that exists somewhere else in memory, not the characters themselves.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A minimal variable declaration contains a type and a name.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two required parts of a minimal variable declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A type and a name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>int x;</code> a legal variable declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. It has both required parts: a type (<code>int</code>) and a name (<code>x</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's missing from the "declaration" <code>x;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The type. A declaration needs both a type and a name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a minimal declaration require an initial value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Only a type and a name are required; initialization is optional.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which parts of <code>double price = 9.99;</code> are the minimum required for a declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The type <code>double</code> and the name <code>price</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The type of a variable determines what kind of values we can assign to the variable and what kind of value it produces when used as an expression.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a variable's type determine?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What values can be assigned to it and what kind of value it produces when used as an expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you assign <code>"hello"</code> to an <code>int</code> variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the variable's type restricts what values can be assigned to it, and <code>"hello"</code> isn't an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is declared <code>double</code>, what kind of value does the expression <code>x</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>A variable's type controls two things. What are they?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What values may be assigned to the variable, and the type of value the variable produces when used as an expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the type of a variable affect how the compiler checks assignments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler only allows assignments of values compatible with the variable's declared type.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The name of a variable allows us to refer to it in assignment expression and as a value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the purpose of a variable's name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets us refer to the variable in assignments and as a value in expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>x = x + 1;</code>, what role does the name <code>x</code> play on each side?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the left, it refers to the variable being assigned; on the right, it refers to the variable's current value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do variables need names?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So we can refer to them in code to assign to them or use their values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two ways you use a variable's name in code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In an assignment (to set its value) and as a value in an expression (to read it).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If variables had no names, what would become impossible?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Referring to them in assignments or expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Two variables can hold references to the same object which allows changes made to the object via one variable to be visible via the other variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is aliasing in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When two variables hold references to the same object, so changes through one are visible through the other.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> refer to the same object and you mutate the object via <code>a</code>, what does <code>b</code> see?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The same change, because both refer to the same underlying object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can two different variables ever affect the same underlying object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, if they both hold references to the same object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can changing an object through one variable affect another variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because reference variables can point to the same object, so there is only one object being modified.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does this aliasing behavior apply to primitive variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Primitive variables store their own copy of the value, so changing one does not affect another.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a variable is declared <code>final</code>, its value cannot be changed once it is initialized.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does declaring a variable <code>final</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once the variable is initialized, its value cannot be changed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to assign to a <code>final</code> variable after initialization?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler reports an error.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might a programmer mark a variable <code>final</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To prevent its value from being changed, making the code safer and intent clearer.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a <code>final</code> variable be given a value at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, exactly once, when it is initialized.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a normal variable and a <code>final</code> variable.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A normal variable can be reassigned any number of times; a <code>final</code> variable can only be assigned once.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>There are two kinds of variables in Java: local and member. Member variables, are further divided into instance and static variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two main kinds of variables in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Local variables and member variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Member variables are divided into which two subcategories?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables and static variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where do the three variable categories fit in the hierarchy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Top level: local vs. member. Member variables split further into instance and static.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is an instance variable a local variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Instance variables are member variables, not local variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the difference between a member variable and a local variable at a high level?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Member variables belong to a class (instance or static); local variables belong to a method or constructor.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Local variables are declared in the body of methods and constructors. These variables may only be used within the method or constructor where they are declared. They are not marked as either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code> because they are not accessible at all outside the method or constructor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where are local variables declared?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the body of a method or constructor.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the scope of a local variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only within the method or constructor where it is declared.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't local variables be marked <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because they aren't accessible outside the method or constructor at all, so access modifiers would be meaningless.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can one method see a local variable declared in another method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Local variables only exist inside the method or constructor that declares them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>private int x;</code> declared inside a method body legal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Local variables cannot have <code>public</code> or <code>private</code> modifiers.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Parameters declared in a method or constructor are also local variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of variable is a method parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A local variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How long does a method parameter exist?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only while the method or constructor is executing, like any other local variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a parameter be marked <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, because parameters are local variables and local variables can't have access modifiers.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>void greet(String name) { ... }</code>, what is <code>name</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A local variable (a parameter) of the <code>greet</code> method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are parameters similar to other local variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are scoped to the method or constructor and are not accessible outside it.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When there is a local variable with the same name as a member variable, the name will refer to the local variable instead of the member variable. This is called "shadowing".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is shadowing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a local variable has the same name as a member variable, causing the name to refer to the local variable instead of the member.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method has a local variable <code>x</code> and the class has a member <code>x</code>, which does the unqualified name <code>x</code> refer to inside the method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The local variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What takes precedence when a local and member variable share a name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The local variable shadows (hides) the member variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does shadowing remove the member variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it just means the unqualified name refers to the local variable within that scope.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can shadowing be confusing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the same name refers to different variables depending on the scope, which can hide the member variable unintentionally.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a instance member variable is shadowed by a local variable it can be referred to with an explicit <code>this.</code> as in <code>this.x</code>. A static member variable can referred to with an explicit <code>ClassName.</code> as in <code>ClassName.SOME_VARIABLE</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you refer to a shadowed instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>this.</code> before the name, as in <code>this.x</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you refer to a shadowed static variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use the class name, as in <code>ClassName.SOME_VARIABLE</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a constructor <code>Point(int x) { this.x = x; }</code>, what does <code>this.x</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The instance variable <code>x</code>, as opposed to the parameter <code>x</code> that shadows it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>this.</code> needed in some assignments but not others?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's only needed when a local variable (often a parameter) shadows the instance variable with the same name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare disambiguating a shadowed instance variable vs. a shadowed static variable.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For an instance variable use <code>this.name</code>; for a static variable use <code>ClassName.name</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Member variable are declared at the top-level of a class and can be marked as <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>. Usually variables will be marked <code>private</code> though sometimes classes define important constants as <code>public static final</code> variables, for instance <code>Math.PI</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where are member variables declared?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the top level of a class, outside any method or constructor.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What access modifiers can member variables have?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code> or <code>private</code> (among others).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are most member variables marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To hide implementation details and keep object state under the control of the class itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When is it common to see a <code>public</code> member variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When defining a constant, declared as <code>public static final</code>, like <code>Math.PI</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do the modifiers in <code>public static final double PI</code> each contribute?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code> makes it accessible anywhere, <code>static</code> makes it belong to the class (not instances), and <code>final</code> makes it a constant that cannot be reassigned.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</invoke>
  <section>
    <title>Expressions</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>An expression is any part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value:</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "evaluate" an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To compute the value that the expression produces.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is every part of a program an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Only those parts that can be evaluated to produce a value are expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a piece of code produces no value at all, can it be called an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. By definition an expression must produce a value when evaluated.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the idea of an expression useful when reading Java code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It gives us a uniform way to talk about any chunk of code that yields a value, regardless of how simple or complex it is.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Literal values, e.g. <code>10</code> or <code>"foo"</code>, evaluate to the value they denote.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a literal value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A value written directly in the source code, such as <code>10</code> or <code>"foo"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the literal <code>10</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The integer value 10 itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when Java evaluates the literal <code>"foo"</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It produces the string value <code>"foo"</code> that the literal denotes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a literal to a variable as an expression.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A literal always evaluates to the same fixed value it denotes, while a variable evaluates to whatever value it currently holds.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>42</code> by itself an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. It is a literal expression that evaluates to the integer 42.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Variables, e.g. <code>x</code> or <code>Math.PI</code>, evaluate to the current value of of the variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a variable expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The current value stored in that variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> holds 7 and later holds 12, what does the expression <code>x</code> evaluate to each time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It evaluates to 7 the first time and 12 the second time, the current value at the moment of evaluation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> a literal or a variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is a variable (a named constant field), not a literal; it evaluates to the current value stored in that field.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you evaluate a variable that has never been assigned a value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In Java, a local variable must be assigned before use or the code will not compile.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do we say a variable "evaluates" to its value rather than "is" its value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the variable is a name, and evaluation is the step that looks up the current value associated with that name.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method calls to non-<code>void</code> methods, e.g. <code>s.substring(1)</code> or <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>, evaluate to the value returned by the method when called with the given arguments.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a non-<code>void</code> method call expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value returned by the method when invoked with the given arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a call to a <code>void</code> method be used as an expression that produces a value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>void</code> methods do not return a value, so such calls cannot be used where a value is required.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> approximately equal to 1.4142135623730951, the value returned by the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>s</code> is <code>"hello"</code>, what does <code>s.substring(1)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The string <code>"ello"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines the type of a method-call expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The declared return type of the method being called.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Object instantiations via the <code>new</code> keyword, e.g. <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code>, evaluate to a reference to a newly created object that has been initialized by running the appropriate constructor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a <code>new</code> expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to a newly created object that has been initialized by running the appropriate constructor.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the constructor play in evaluating a <code>new</code> expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It initializes the freshly allocated object before the reference is produced.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code> produce the object itself or a reference to it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the newly created object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if the constructor throws an exception during a <code>new</code> expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No reference is produced; the expression does not complete normally and the exception propagates.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a <code>new</code> expression to a literal expression.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A literal denotes a fixed value, while a <code>new</code> expression allocates and initializes a fresh object each time it is evaluated.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Array access expressions, e.g <code>xs[0]</code>, evaluate to the value stored at the given position in the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does an array access expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value stored at the specified index in the array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>xs</code> is <code>{10, 20, 30}</code>, what does <code>xs[0]</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>10, the element at index 0.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you evaluate <code>xs[i]</code> with an index outside the array's bounds?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of an array access expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element type of the array being indexed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the index in an array access itself an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Any <code>int</code>-typed expression may be used as the index.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Compound expressions made up of expressions and operators, e.g. <code>x + 2</code>, evaluate to a value determined by the operator and its operands.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a compound expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression made up of sub-expressions combined with operators.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines the value of a compound expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The operator applied to the values produced by its operands.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is 5, what does the compound expression <code>x + 2</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>7.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the operands of a compound expression themselves be compound expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Expressions nest, so operands can be arbitrarily complex sub-expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a compound expression different from a literal expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A literal is a single value written in code, while a compound expression combines multiple expressions with operators to compute a new value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each expression has a type which is determined by the types of its sub-expressions and the operators involved. The type describes the kind of values it can produce.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Does every expression in Java have a type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Every expression has a type describing the kind of values it can produce.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines the type of a compound expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The types of its sub-expressions together with the operators involved.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the "type" of an expression describe?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The kind of values the expression can produce when evaluated.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is an <code>int</code>, what is the type of the expression <code>x + 2</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>, because both operands are <code>int</code> and <code>+</code> on two <code>int</code>s yields an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java care about the type of every expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So it can check at compile time that expressions are used in contexts where their values make sense.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Anywhere a value of a given type is needed we can use any expression that produces values of that type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When Java needs a value of a given type, what kinds of code can supply it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any expression that produces values of that type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method parameter expects an <code>int</code>, can you pass <code>3 + 4</code> instead of just <code>7</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Any <code>int</code>-typed expression, including <code>3 + 4</code>, works anywhere an <code>int</code> value is needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What principle lets us freely replace a literal with a more complex expression of the same type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Anywhere a value of a given type is needed, any expression producing that type may be used.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must match between an expression and the context where it is used?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The type of the expression must match the type required by the context.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does this principle make programs composable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because simple expressions can be swapped for more complex ones of the same type without changing where they are used.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Arithmetic expressions</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arithmetic expressions are expressions that produce an or <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an arithmetic expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression that produces an <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What two numeric types can an AP CSA arithmetic expression produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> and <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a <code>String</code> concatenation with <code>+</code> considered an arithmetic expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Arithmetic expressions produce numeric values, not strings.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an arithmetic expression evaluate to a <code>boolean</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Arithmetic expressions only produce <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>3 + 4.0</code> an arithmetic expression? What type does it produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, and it produces a <code>double</code> because one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The arithmetic operators consist of <code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the five arithmetic operators in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>%</code> operator compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The remainder left after dividing the left operand by the right operand.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>17 % 5</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>2.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>/</code> differ from <code>%</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>/</code> produces the quotient of a division, while <code>%</code> produces the remainder.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>**</code> a Java arithmetic operator for exponentiation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Java has no <code>**</code> operator; use <code>Math.pow</code> instead.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An arithmetic operation on two <code>int</code>s will evaluate to an <code>int</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of an arithmetic expression whose operands are both <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>7 / 2</code> evaluate to in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>3, because integer division truncates toward zero.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>1 / 2</code> give 0 in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both operands are <code>int</code>, so the result is an <code>int</code> and the fractional part is dropped.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you force a floating-point division between two <code>int</code> variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Cast at least one operand to <code>double</code>, e.g. <code>(double) a / b</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the result type of <code>3 + 4</code> and <code>3 + 4.0</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3 + 4</code> is an <code>int</code>; <code>3 + 4.0</code> is a <code>double</code> because one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An arithmetic operation with at least one <code>double</code> value will evaluate to a <code>double</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of an arithmetic expression that has at least one <code>double</code> operand?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>7 / 2.0</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3.5</code> as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you mix an <code>int</code> and a <code>double</code> with <code>+</code>, what happens to the <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is automatically converted to a <code>double</code> before the addition is performed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the results of <code>5 / 2</code> and <code>5.0 / 2</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5 / 2</code> is the <code>int</code> 2; <code>5.0 / 2</code> is the <code>double</code> 2.5.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does adding even a single <code>double</code> operand "upgrade" the result type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So no precision is lost: the <code>int</code> can be represented as a <code>double</code>, but not vice versa.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Operators can be used to construct compound expressions.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do operators let you build out of simpler expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compound expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of using operators to build a compound expression from smaller ones.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(a + b) * c</code> combines <code>a</code>, <code>b</code>, and <code>c</code> using <code>+</code> and <code>*</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the operands of a compound expression themselves be compound expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, expressions can be nested to any depth.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you combine two <code>int</code> expressions with an arithmetic operator?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You get another <code>int</code>-typed expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are compound expressions useful?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They let you compute complex values in a single step rather than breaking every calculation into separate statements.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>During evaluation, operands are associated with operators according to operator precedence to determine how they are grouped.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What rule decides how operands and operators are grouped during evaluation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Operator precedence.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>2 + 3 * 4</code>, which operation happens first, and why?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3 * 4</code>, because <code>*</code> has higher precedence than <code>+</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>2 + 3 * 4</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>14.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you override the default precedence in an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use parentheses to explicitly group sub-expressions, e.g. <code>(2 + 3) * 4</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>2 + 3 * 4</code> with <code>(2 + 3) * 4</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first evaluates to 14 using operator precedence; the second evaluates to 20 because parentheses force the addition first.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An attempt to divide an integer by zero will result in an <code>ArithmeticException</code> to occur.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you divide an <code>int</code> by zero in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArithmeticException</code> is thrown at runtime.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is integer division by zero a compile-time error?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is a runtime error that throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What exception type signals integer division by zero?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>%</code> with a right operand of zero throw the same exception as <code>/</code> does?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. <code>int</code> modulo by zero also throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare integer division by zero with <code>double</code> division by zero.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Integer division by zero throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>; <code>double</code> division by zero yields <code>Infinity</code>, <code>-Infinity</code>, or <code>NaN</code> instead.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The casting operators <code>(int)</code> and <code>(double)</code> produce numeric values of the specified type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do the casting operators <code>(int)</code> and <code>(double)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They produce a numeric value of the specified type from their operand.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the syntax for casting a value <code>x</code> to <code>double</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(double) x</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a cast change the original variable's value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It produces a new value of the target type; the original variable is unchanged.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of the expression <code>(int) 3.7</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare casting with automatic conversion.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Casting is an explicit conversion written by the programmer; automatic conversion happens implicitly when Java widens a narrower numeric type to a wider one.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Casting a <code>double</code> to an <code>int</code> produces an <code>int</code> with any fractional part (the digits to the right of the decimal point) truncated.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does casting a <code>double</code> to an <code>int</code> do to the fractional part?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It truncates it, dropping any digits to the right of the decimal point.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(int) 3.7</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>3.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(int) -3.7</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>-3, because truncation drops the fractional part rather than rounding down.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is truncation the same as rounding?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Truncation simply discards the fractional part, while rounding chooses the nearest integer.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>(int) 3.9</code> and <code>Math.round(3.9)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(int) 3.9</code> truncates to 3, while <code>Math.round(3.9)</code> rounds to 4.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Casting an <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> produces a double with the same mathematical value since all <code>int</code> values are exactly representable as a <code>double</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does casting an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> with the same mathematical value as the original <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is no precision lost when casting <code>int</code> to <code>double</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because every <code>int</code> value is exactly representable as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(double) 5</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the safety of casting <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> with casting <code>double</code> to <code>int</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> to <code>double</code> preserves the value exactly; <code>double</code> to <code>int</code> can lose the fractional part through truncation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>a</code> is 5 and <code>b</code> is 2, how does <code>(double) a / b</code> differ from <code>a / b</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(double) a / b</code> evaluates to 2.5, while <code>a / b</code> evaluates to the <code>int</code> 2.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Using an <code>int</code> where a <code>double</code> is expected, without a cast, causes the <code>int</code> value to be automatically converted to a <code>double</code> value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you use an <code>int</code> where a <code>double</code> is expected?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>int</code> is automatically converted to a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is an explicit cast needed to pass an <code>int</code> to a method expecting a <code>double</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Java performs the conversion automatically.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>double d = 5;</code>, what value does <code>d</code> hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5.0</code>, the <code>double</code> value automatically converted from the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java allow automatic <code>int</code>-to-<code>double</code> conversion but not the reverse?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because widening from <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> is lossless, while narrowing from <code>double</code> to <code>int</code> can lose the fractional part.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>Math.sqrt(9)</code>, what happens to the <code>int</code> argument?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is automatically converted to the <code>double</code> <code>9.0</code> before <code>sqrt</code> runs.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Values of type <code>double</code> can be rounded to the nearest <code>int</code> by <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code> or <code>(int)(x - 0.5)</code> for negative numbers.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How can you round a positive <code>double</code> <code>x</code> to the nearest <code>int</code> using a cast?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code> round to the nearest integer for positive <code>x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Adding 0.5 shifts values at or above the halfway point into the next integer before truncation drops the fractional part.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What expression rounds a negative <code>double</code> <code>x</code> to the nearest <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(int)(x - 0.5)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do you subtract 0.5 instead of adding it for negative numbers?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because truncation rounds toward zero, so for negatives you need to push the value further from zero before truncating to get nearest-integer rounding.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(int)(3.7 + 0.5)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>4.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</content>
</invoke>
  <section>
    <title>Boolean expressions</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A boolean expression is any expression that results in a `boolean` value. The values used in the expression may be `boolean`s or other kinds of values. For instance, `x &gt; 10` is a `boolean` expression even though `x` must be a number and `a == b` always evaluates to a `boolean` even though `a` and `b` could be any type of values.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What defines a boolean expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any expression that results in a <code>boolean</code> value, regardless of the types of the sub-expressions involved.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>x &gt; 10</code> a boolean expression even though <code>x</code> is a number?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. The operands are numeric, but the result of the comparison is a <code>boolean</code>, so the whole expression is a boolean expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you evaluate <code>a == b</code> where <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It still produces a <code>boolean</code> result, so it counts as a boolean expression even though neither operand is a <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Suppose a method is declared to return <code>boolean</code>. Is a call to it a boolean expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Any expression whose result is a <code>boolean</code> value qualifies, including method calls that return <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a boolean expression with an arithmetic expression.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are expressions that produce values, but a boolean expression specifically produces a <code>boolean</code> (<code>true</code> or <code>false</code>), while an arithmetic expression produces a numeric value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Boolean expressions are made from `boolean` literals, `boolean` variables, methods that return `boolean`, and expressions involving logical operators, equality operators, relational operators.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the building blocks of a boolean expression in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code> literals, <code>boolean</code> variables, methods returning <code>boolean</code>, and expressions using logical, equality, or relational operators.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two <code>boolean</code> literals in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which three categories of operators can produce a <code>boolean</code> result?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Logical operators, equality operators, and relational operators.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method returns an <code>int</code>, can a call to it by itself be a boolean expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Only a method that returns <code>boolean</code> produces a boolean expression on its own; an <code>int</code>-returning call would need to be combined with a relational or equality operator.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a boolean expression that uses a <code>boolean</code> variable combined with a relational operator.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Something like <code>done || x &lt; 10</code>, where <code>done</code> is a <code>boolean</code> variable and <code>x &lt; 10</code> is a relational expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Logical operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Logical operators operate on `boolean` values and produce a `boolean` value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of values do logical operators take as operands, and what do they produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They operate on <code>boolean</code> values and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you apply <code>&amp;&amp;</code> to two <code>int</code> values in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Logical operators require <code>boolean</code> operands; using <code>int</code>s produces a compile error.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the result type of <code>a || b</code> when <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are <code>boolean</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast a logical operator with a relational operator in terms of input types.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Relational operators take numeric operands and return <code>boolean</code>; logical operators take <code>boolean</code> operands and return <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can logical operators be chained, like <code>a &amp;&amp; b &amp;&amp; c</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each application produces a <code>boolean</code>, which is a valid operand for the next logical operator.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The logical operators in Java are `!` (not), `&amp;&amp;` (and), and `||` (or).</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name the three logical operators in Java.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> (not), <code>&amp;&amp;</code> (and), and <code>||</code> (or).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which logical operator is unary?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> (not); it takes a single <code>boolean</code> operand and flips its value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>true &amp;&amp; false</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code>. <code>&amp;&amp;</code> is true only when both operands are true.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>false || true</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>. <code>||</code> is true when at least one operand is true.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code> differ conceptually?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> requires both operands to be true to produce true; <code>||</code> requires only one operand to be true.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`!` is the highest precedence, followed by `&amp;&amp;`, followed by `||`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the precedence ordering of Java's logical operators?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> is highest, then <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, then <code>||</code> is lowest.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>!a &amp;&amp; b</code> parsed given precedence rules?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As <code>(!a) &amp;&amp; b</code>, because <code>!</code> binds tighter than <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>a || b &amp;&amp; c</code> parsed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As <code>a || (b &amp;&amp; c)</code>, because <code>&amp;&amp;</code> has higher precedence than <code>||</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you want <code>||</code> to be evaluated before <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, what do you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use parentheses, e.g. <code>(a || b) &amp;&amp; c</code>, to override the default precedence.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the precedence of <code>!</code> to the precedence of <code>||</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> has the highest logical precedence and <code>||</code> the lowest, so <code>!</code> is applied to its operand long before any surrounding <code>||</code> is evaluated.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When the result of a logical expression using `&amp;&amp;` or `||` can be determined by evaluating only the first operand, the second is not evaluated. This is known as short-circuited evaluation.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is short-circuited evaluation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a logical expression using <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code> can be decided from the first operand, Java skips evaluating the second operand.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>false &amp;&amp; someMethod()</code>, is <code>someMethod()</code> called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Since the left side is <code>false</code>, the whole <code>&amp;&amp;</code> must be <code>false</code>, so the right side is skipped.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>true || someMethod()</code>, is <code>someMethod()</code> called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. The left side being <code>true</code> determines the <code>||</code> result, so the right side is not evaluated.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is short-circuiting useful when the second operand might crash?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can guard a risky expression with a safe check, e.g. <code>s != null &amp;&amp; s.length() &gt; 0</code>, so the risky call only runs when it is safe.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code> short-circuit behavior.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> short-circuits when the first operand is <code>false</code>; <code>||</code> short-circuits when the first operand is <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>De Morgan's Laws allows us to transform some boolean expressions into equivalent expressions. `!a &amp;&amp; !b = !(a || b)` `!a || !b = !(a &amp;&amp; b)`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do De Morgan's Laws let you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Transform certain boolean expressions into equivalent forms, specifically by distributing a <code>!</code> across <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>State De Morgan's Law for <code>!(a || b)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!(a || b)</code> is equivalent to <code>!a &amp;&amp; !b</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>State De Morgan's Law for <code>!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code> is equivalent to <code>!a || !b</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Rewrite <code>!(x &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; y &gt; 0)</code> without the outer <code>!</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using De Morgan's Laws: <code>x &lt;= 0 || y &lt;= 0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful to transform a boolean expression with De Morgan's Laws?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can make conditions easier to read, remove a confusing outer negation, or expose a form that matches existing code.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Truth tables can be used to prove `boolean` identities, i.e. different expressions that are equivalent in the sense that for all possible combinations of values for the variables in the expressions they evaluate to the same value. A trivial example of a pair of equivalent expressions is: `a &amp;&amp; true` and `a`. More complex identities include things like De Morgan's Laws. For more details see [Boolean algebra summary]</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a truth table used for?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To prove that two boolean expressions are equivalent by checking that they produce the same result for every combination of input values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean for two boolean expressions to be equivalent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For every possible combination of values of their variables, both expressions evaluate to the same <code>boolean</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>a &amp;&amp; true</code> equivalent to <code>a</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether <code>a</code> is <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>, <code>a &amp;&amp; true</code> has the same value as <code>a</code>, so they match in every row of the truth table.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many rows does a truth table need for an expression in three boolean variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Eight rows: one for each combination of <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> across the three variables (2 to the 3rd power).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you make a truth table for both sides of a De Morgan's Law?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both sides yield identical columns for all input combinations, proving the identity.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Equality operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Both primitive and reference values can be compared for equality using the equality operators `==` and `!=`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which operators are the equality operators in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code> and <code>!=</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you use <code>==</code> on reference values like objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. <code>==</code> can compare both primitive and reference values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>!=</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Not equal." It returns <code>true</code> when the two operands are not equal using <code>==</code>'s notion of equality.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you compare an <code>int</code> and a <code>double</code> with <code>==</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is allowed because both are primitives; Java compares their numeric values after any needed conversion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>==</code> on primitives versus on references.</p></question>
        <answer><p>On primitives <code>==</code> compares values directly; on references it compares whether the two variables refer to the same object.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>However two object references are only `==` when they both reference the same object or when they are both `null`. This may not, however, be the notion of "the same" that you care about when you are comparing two objects.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When are two object references <code>==</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only when they refer to the same object in memory, or when both are <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two <code>String</code> objects have the same characters but were created separately, what does <code>==</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It may return <code>false</code>, because they are different objects even though their contents match.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>==</code> always the right way to compare objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>==</code> tests identity; often you want to test whether the objects are "the same" in terms of content, which is a different question.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens with <code>null == null</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It evaluates to <code>true</code>, since both references are <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the meaning of <code>==</code> for primitives versus objects.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For primitives it asks "are the values the same?"; for objects it asks "are these references to the very same object?".</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All classes have an `equals` method inherited from `Object` and often overridden by classes to provide a way to determine if two instances of the class are equivalent. For example, two `String` objects with the same character content are `equals` even when they are not `==`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does every class get its <code>equals</code> method from?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>Object</code>, the superclass of all classes in Java.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do many classes override <code>equals</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To give a meaningful, content-based notion of equivalence for their instances rather than the default reference comparison.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you compare two <code>String</code>s with the same characters using <code>.equals</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns <code>true</code>, even if <code>==</code> would return <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>String a = new String("hi"); String b = new String("hi");</code>. What do <code>a == b</code> and <code>a.equals(b)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>a == b</code> is <code>false</code> (different objects); <code>a.equals(b)</code> is <code>true</code> (same content).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>==</code> and <code>.equals</code> for objects.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code> checks whether two references point to the same object; <code>.equals</code> checks whether two objects are equivalent by whatever rule the class defines.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `==` operator is sometimes pronounced "equals equals" to distinguish it from the `equals` method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>==</code> sometimes pronounced out loud?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Equals equals."</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why use the pronunciation "equals equals" for <code>==</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To distinguish it in speech from the <code>equals</code> method, which has a different meaning.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone says "a dot equals b" versus "a equals equals b", which refers to the method and which refers to the operator?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"a dot equals b" refers to the <code>equals</code> method; "a equals equals b" refers to the <code>==</code> operator.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you confuse <code>==</code> with <code>.equals</code> on objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You may end up checking reference identity when you meant to check value equivalence, leading to subtle bugs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the syntactic forms of the two kinds of equality checks on objects.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The operator form is <code>a == b</code>; the method form is <code>a.equals(b)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Relational operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Relational operators operate on numeric values and produce a `boolean` value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of values do relational operators take, and what do they produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They take numeric operands and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you use relational operators directly on two <code>boolean</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Relational operators require numeric operands.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the result type of <code>5 &lt; 10</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code> — specifically <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to combine the result of a relational comparison with another condition. What kind of operator do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A logical operator like <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code>, because the relational expression produces a <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare relational operators with logical operators in terms of input types.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Relational operators consume numbers and produce <code>boolean</code>; logical operators consume <code>boolean</code>s and produce <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Numeric values can be compared using the relational operators `&lt;`, `&gt;`, `&lt;=`, and `&gt;=` which evaluate to `true` if their left hand operand is less than, greater than, less than or equal to, or greater than or equal to the right hand operand. E.g. `10 &lt; 20` evaluates to `true`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the four relational operators in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;=</code>, and <code>&gt;=</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>a &lt;= b</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It evaluates to <code>true</code> when <code>a</code> is less than or equal to <code>b</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>10 &lt; 20</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to check that <code>x</code> is strictly greater than <code>y</code>. Which operator do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&gt;</code>, as in <code>x &gt; y</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&lt;</code> is true only when the left side is strictly less than the right; <code>&lt;=</code> is also true when the two sides are equal.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You can't chain relational operators in Java the way you can in math. So rather than writing `0 &lt;= x &lt; 10` you have to combine two relational expressions with the logical operator `&amp;&amp;`, writing instead `0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can you write <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java the way you would in math?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Java does not allow chained relational operators.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the correct way to express "x is between 0 and 10" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Combine two relational expressions with <code>&amp;&amp;</code>: <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to compile <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You get a compile error, because the first comparison yields a <code>boolean</code>, and <code>&lt;</code> cannot compare a <code>boolean</code> to an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java reject chained relational operators?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each relational operator produces a <code>boolean</code>, and relational operators require numeric operands, so chaining leads to a type mismatch.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the math notation <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> with the Java equivalent.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The math form uses implicit conjunction; Java makes the conjunction explicit with <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, as in <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</content>
</invoke>
  <section>
    <title>Assignment operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Assignments in Java are technically expressions that produce a value but normally we care more about their side effect, namely changing the value the variable or array element being assigned to.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Are assignments in Java statements or expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are technically expressions that produce a value, though we usually care about their side effect.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "side effect" of a Java assignment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Changing the value stored in the variable or array element being assigned to.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can you write <code>x = y = 0;</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because assignment is an expression that produces a value, so <code>y = 0</code> yields <code>0</code>, which is then assigned to <code>x</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When we use an assignment, do we usually care about its value or its side effect?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its side effect - updating the variable or array element.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do assignment expressions differ from, say, arithmetic expressions like <code>a + b</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Arithmetic expressions are evaluated purely for their value, while assignment expressions are evaluated mainly for the side effect of storing a new value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The only assignable places in Java are variables (local or member) and array access expressions, e.g. `x`, `obj.someField`, and `nums[0]`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What three kinds of "places" can appear on the left side of an assignment in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Local variables, member (field) variables, and array access expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an array access expression that is assignable.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>nums[0]</code> - or any <code>array[index]</code> expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>obj.someField</code> a legal target for assignment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, member field access is one of the assignable places in Java.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to assign to something like <code>x + 1</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is a compile error - <code>x + 1</code> is not an assignable place; only variables and array elements are.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an assignable place to a regular expression - what distinguishes them?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An assignable place names a storage location (variable or array element) that can be updated, while a regular expression just produces a value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The assignment operator `=` allows a program to initialize or change the value stored in a variable or an array element. The value of the expression on the right of the `=` is stored in the variable or array element referenced on the left. The value of of an assignment expression is the value that was assigned.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>=</code> operator do in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It initializes or changes the value stored in a variable or array element, storing the right-hand value into the left-hand location.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>x = 5 + 3;</code>, which side is evaluated first and what gets stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The right side is evaluated first, producing <code>8</code>, which is then stored in <code>x</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the value of the expression <code>x = 10</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value that was assigned - in this case, <code>10</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>int a = b = c = 0;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>c</code> is assigned <code>0</code> (value <code>0</code>), then <code>b</code> is assigned that value, then <code>a</code> is assigned that value - all three end up as <code>0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does the <code>=</code> operator flow right-to-left or left-to-right?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The right-hand expression is evaluated and its value flows into the left-hand location.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Compound assignment operators (`+=`, `−=`, `*=`, `/=`, `%=`) can be used to assign a new value to a variable or array element computed from the old value. For instance `x += 2` is equivalent to `x = x + 2`. The value of a compound assignment expression is the new value of the variable or array element.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a compound assignment operator?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An operator like <code>+=</code>, <code>-=</code>, <code>*=</code>, <code>/=</code>, or <code>%=</code> that computes a new value from the old value and assigns it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>x += 2</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>x = x + 2</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>10</code>, what is the value of the expression <code>x *= 3</code>, and what is <code>x</code> afterward?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The expression's value is <code>30</code> (the new value), and <code>x</code> is now <code>30</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the value of a compound assignment differ from the value of a plain assignment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are the same kind of thing: both yield the value that was stored in the variable. For a compound assignment that's the newly computed value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want to reduce <code>score</code> by <code>5</code>. Write it using a compound assignment.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>score -= 5;</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The increment operator (`++`) and decrement operator (`−−`) are used to add 1 or subtract 1 from the value of a variable or an array element. For instance `x++` equivalent to `x += 1` or `x = x + 1`. The value of a `++` or `--` is the value of the variable or array element before it was incremented or decremented.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do <code>++</code> and <code>--</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They add 1 to or subtract 1 from the value of a variable or array element.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p><code>x++</code> is equivalent to which longer forms?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>x += 1</code> or <code>x = x + 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>5</code>, what is the value of the expression <code>x++</code>, and what is <code>x</code> afterward?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The expression's value is <code>5</code> (the value before), and <code>x</code> is now <code>6</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the value of <code>x++</code> differ from the value of <code>x += 1</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>x++</code> yields the old value of <code>x</code>, while <code>x += 1</code> yields the new value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to <code>nums[i]</code> when you write <code>nums[i]--</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The array element at index <code>i</code> is decreased by 1; the expression's value is the element's value before the decrement.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Note that `=` (one equals sign) is the assignment operator and `==` (two equals signs) is the equality comparison operator. If you mix them up, you'll get either compiler errors or incorrect and confusing behavior from your program.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the difference between <code>=</code> and <code>==</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>=</code> assigns a value to a variable; <code>==</code> compares two values for equality.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What goes wrong if you write <code>if (x = 5)</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's a compile error because <code>x = 5</code> produces an <code>int</code>, not the <code>boolean</code> an <code>if</code> requires.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is mixing up <code>=</code> and <code>==</code> dangerous?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can cause compiler errors or, worse, silently incorrect behavior that is hard to debug.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which operator would you use to check whether two <code>int</code>s are equal?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code>, the equality comparison operator.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you meant to compare <code>count</code> to <code>0</code> but wrote <code>count = 0</code>. What are the consequences?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You overwrite <code>count</code> with <code>0</code> instead of comparing, changing the program's state and likely causing confusing, incorrect behavior.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Methods</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Procedural abstraction means hiding how a value is computed or how an effect is achieved allowing a programmer to use a method without needing to know exactly how the method is written.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is procedural abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Hiding how a value is computed or how an effect is achieved, so a programmer can use a method without knowing exactly how it's written.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does procedural abstraction let a programmer avoid thinking about?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The internal details of how a method computes its value or achieves its effect.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you call <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>, how does procedural abstraction help you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can use the result without knowing the algorithm Java uses internally to compute the square root.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is procedural abstraction different from just reusing code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Reuse is a benefit, but abstraction specifically refers to hiding implementation details so the caller doesn't need to know them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is procedural abstraction important for managing complexity?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets programmers reason about a method by its behavior alone, without keeping all of its implementation details in mind.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In Java the unit of procedural abstraction is the method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the unit of procedural abstraction in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In Java, where does procedural abstraction live?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In methods - each method packages up some computation or effect behind a name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that the method is Java's "unit" of procedural abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Methods are the building blocks Java gives you for hiding how something is computed or done.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone asks "how do I create a new abstraction in Java?" what's a basic answer?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Write a method that hides some computation or effect behind a named, reusable interface.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare: in Java, methods are to procedural abstraction as what are to data abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Classes (and their fields/objects) are the unit of data abstraction, while methods are the unit of procedural abstraction.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods allow us to "decompose" or break down a large problem into smaller sub-problems by writing methods that call other methods that each solve various sub-problems.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "decompose" a problem using methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Breaking a large problem into smaller sub-problems, each solved by its own method, which may call other methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is decomposition helpful when solving big problems?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Smaller sub-problems are easier to understand, solve, test, and reason about than one giant monolithic problem.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when methods call other methods during decomposition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each method handles a piece of the work and delegates other pieces to helper methods, building up the full solution.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you need to compute the average grade per student from a list. How might you decompose it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Write one method to sum a student's grades, another to count them, and another that uses both to compute the average.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does method decomposition relate to procedural abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each decomposed sub-problem becomes a method, and procedural abstraction lets callers use it without worrying about its internal details.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>We can use methods provided to us by Java (as in the `Math` methods such as `Math.sqrt`) and also methods that we write ourselves.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two kinds of methods can a Java program use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Methods provided by Java (like <code>Math.sqrt</code>) and methods that we write ourselves.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a Java-provided method.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.sqrt</code>, or any method in the <code>Math</code> class such as <code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, etc.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a difference in how you call a library method versus one you wrote yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - the calling syntax is the same; the only difference is who wrote the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful that you can mix library methods and your own methods freely?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can build on top of Java's provided functionality instead of reinventing everything, while still writing custom behavior where needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What class in Java provides common mathematical methods like <code>sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>Math</code> class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>We can use methods without knowing exactly how they are implemented but it is also useful to write our own method to hide details in one part of our code even though we have to deal with those details elsewhere.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Do you have to know how a method is implemented in order to use it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - you can use methods based only on what they do, without understanding their implementation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might you write a method to hide details even when you're the one who has to write those details?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that the details appear in only one place and the rest of your code can stay clean and focused on its own concerns.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the benefit of writing your own method to hide details you still have to handle?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It isolates complexity to one place, making the rest of your code simpler and easier to understand.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you have messy string parsing logic scattered throughout your program. What should you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Extract the parsing into its own method so the details are handled in one place and callers just use the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare using a library method versus writing your own method for abstraction.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both hide details from the caller; with library methods someone else already wrote them, while with your own methods you write the details once and then forget about them elsewhere.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The code in one method can call other methods, allowing us to build layers of abstractions.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What can code inside one method do with other methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can call them, which lets us build layers of abstractions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "build layers of abstractions"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Higher-level methods are built by calling lower-level methods, each hiding more detail from the layer above.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>printReport</code> method calls <code>formatRow</code>, which calls <code>formatNumber</code>. What does this illustrate?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Layered abstractions - each method is expressed in terms of lower-level helpers, hiding details from the higher-level methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are layered abstractions useful for managing complex programs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each layer only has to understand the layer directly below it, keeping any individual piece of code simple.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does method-to-method calling relate to problem decomposition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Decomposition produces sub-problems solved by methods, and methods calling other methods is exactly how those pieces fit back together.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Method structure</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method signatures must specify three things: the return type, the name of the method, and the method's parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What three things does a Java method signature specify?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The return type, the method's name, and its parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>int add(int a, int b)</code>, identify the three parts of the signature.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Return type: <code>int</code>; name: <code>add</code>; parameters: <code>int a, int b</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does a method signature need the return type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So the compiler and callers know what kind of value the method produces.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's missing from this "signature": <code>add(int a, int b)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The return type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a method signature to a function's contract - what does the signature tell a caller?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It tells the caller the method's name, what types of arguments to pass, and what type of value (if any) to expect back.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The return type specifies the kind of value the method returns. The special return type `void` indicates that a method does not return any value. All non-`void` methods must return a value of the specified type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the return type of a method specify?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The kind of value the method returns to its caller.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the special return type <code>void</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That the method does not return any value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must every non-<code>void</code> method do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Return a value of the type declared as its return type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if an <code>int</code> method has a path that doesn't return anything?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The code won't compile - non-<code>void</code> methods must return a value of the specified type on every path.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>void</code> and <code>int</code> as return types.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> means the method must return an <code>int</code> value; <code>void</code> means the method returns no value at all.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods with `void` as their return type are called "`void` methods" and are called only for the effects they have, such as printing to the screen or changing the state of an object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "<code>void</code> method"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method whose return type is <code>void</code>, meaning it returns no value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why would you call a <code>void</code> method if it doesn't return anything?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For its side effects - like printing to the screen or changing an object's state.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give two examples of side effects a <code>void</code> method might perform.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Printing text to the screen and changing the state of an object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write <code>int x = printHello();</code> where <code>printHello</code> is <code>void</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - you can't assign the result of a <code>void</code> method to a variable because it produces no value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how you'd use a <code>void</code> method vs. a non-<code>void</code> method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Non-<code>void</code> methods can be used anywhere a value is needed; <code>void</code> methods can only be called as statements for their effects.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method parameters are variables and thus must be specified with a type and a name.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are method parameters in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Variables declared in the method's signature, each specified with a type and a name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What two things must you specify for each parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its type and its name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's wrong with the parameter list <code>(a, b)</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's missing the types - each parameter needs both a type and a name, like <code>(int a, int b)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do parameters need names as well as types?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So code inside the method can refer to the passed-in values using those names.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a parameter to a local variable.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Parameters are essentially local variables that are initialized automatically from the caller's arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods that take no arguments are written with an empty parameter list consisting of just a pair of parentheses.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you write a method that takes no arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With an empty parameter list - just a pair of parentheses, like <code>foo()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you simply omit the parentheses for a method with no parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - the parentheses are required even when there are no parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>void greet()</code> tell you about the method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns nothing and takes no parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a method that prints the current time. What would its parameter list look like?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An empty pair of parentheses, since the method needs no inputs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>foo()</code> and <code>foo(int x)</code> in terms of argument requirements.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>foo()</code> takes no arguments, while <code>foo(int x)</code> requires one <code>int</code> argument.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of the method follows the signature and is enclosed in a pair of `{}`s.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does a method's body go relative to its signature?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body follows the signature and is enclosed in a pair of <code>{}</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What delimits the start and end of a method body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Curly braces: <code>{</code> and <code>}</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you omit the braces if the method body is just one statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - unlike some constructs, method bodies always require braces.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the overall shape of a Java method declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A signature followed by a body enclosed in <code>{}</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a method body to an <code>if</code> block visually.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both use curly braces to enclose code, but a method body always needs braces while a single-statement <code>if</code> technically doesn't.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Code within the body of a method can refer to the parameters declared in the method signature as well as any local variables declared in the method and any `static` variables declared in the class. Code in instance methods can also refer to any instance variables defined in the class and the special variable `this` which refers to the object on which the method was invoked.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What variables can any method body refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its parameters, its local variables, and any <code>static</code> variables declared in the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What additional things can an instance method access that a <code>static</code> method cannot?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables of the class and the special variable <code>this</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>this</code> refer to inside an instance method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object on which the method was invoked.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're in a <code>static</code> method and try to use <code>this</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - <code>this</code> is only available in instance methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the variable access of a <code>static</code> method vs. an instance method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can access parameters, locals, and <code>static</code> variables; only instance methods can also access instance variables and <code>this</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Method calls</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method calls consist of a reference to the method and a possibly empty argument list consisting of a comma-separated list of expressions, e.g. `foo(10, "some string")`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two parts of a method call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the method and a (possibly empty) argument list of comma-separated expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>foo(10, "some string")</code>, what is the argument list?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>10, "some string"</code> - a comma-separated list of two expressions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the argument list of a method call be empty?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - you just write an empty pair of parentheses like <code>foo()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of things can appear in an argument list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Expressions - literals, variable references, arithmetic, other method calls, anything that evaluates to a value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are multiple arguments separated in a method call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By commas.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The expressions in the argument list are evaluated to get the values that are passed as the arguments to the method. When the method runs the parameters declared in the method signature are initialized to the values of the corresponding arguments, with the first parameter getting the value of the first argument, and so on.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the expressions in an argument list at call time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are evaluated, and the resulting values become the arguments passed to the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are a method's parameters initialized when it runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each parameter is initialized to the value of the corresponding argument, in order - first parameter from first argument, and so on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>add(2 + 3, x * y)</code>, what exactly gets passed to <code>add</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The values produced by evaluating <code>2 + 3</code> and <code>x * y</code>, not the expressions themselves.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does argument order matter when matching up with parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - the first argument goes to the first parameter, the second to the second, and so on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare passing <code>foo(x)</code> to <code>foo(x + 0)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both evaluate their argument expression and pass the resulting value; the method can't tell the difference.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The arguments passed to a constructor or method call must be compatible with the types identified in the parameter list.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What must be true about the types of arguments in a method or constructor call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They must be compatible with the types declared in the parameter list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you pass a <code>String</code> to a parameter declared as <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A compile error - the types are not compatible.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you pass an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - <code>int</code> is compatible with <code>double</code> because it can be automatically widened.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method takes <code>(int, String)</code> and you call it with <code>("hello", 5)</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - the argument types don't match the parameter types in order.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java enforce type compatibility at call sites?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To catch mistakes at compile time and guarantee the method receives values of the kinds it knows how to work with.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arguments are passed to methods by copying values. This means that there is no way for code in a method to change the value of local variable in the method that called it.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are arguments passed to methods in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By copying values - the parameter gets a copy of the argument's value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a method change the value of a local variable in its caller?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - because arguments are passed by copying, reassigning a parameter inside the method has no effect on the caller's variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>void zero(int n) { n = 0; }</code> called as <code>zero(x)</code>. What happens to <code>x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing - <code>x</code> still has its original value because only a copy of its value was passed in.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does "pass by copying values" prevent a method from modifying caller locals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The parameter is a separate variable that just starts with a copy of the caller's value; changes to the parameter never touch the caller's variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare pass-by-value to a hypothetical pass-by-reference for primitives.</p></question>
        <answer><p>With pass-by-value (Java's approach), the method can't change the caller's variable; with pass-by-reference, changes inside the method would be visible to the caller.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Recall, however, that the value of a reference type is the reference itself; this means code in a method or constructor that is passed a reference to a mutable object can use the reference to alter the state of the object and those changes will be visible to other code that also has a reference to that object. As a matter of good coding practice, methods should not modify mutable objects passed as arguments unless doing so is an inherent part of the method's purpose.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "value" of a reference type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The reference itself - essentially a pointer to the object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Even though Java passes arguments by copying, how can a method still affect the caller's data?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If the argument is a reference to a mutable object, both method and caller hold references to the same object, so state changes made through the method's copy of the reference are visible to the caller.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the good-coding-practice rule about modifying mutable objects passed as arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Methods shouldn't modify them unless doing so is an inherent part of the method's purpose.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method takes an array and sorts it in place. Is that acceptable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, if sorting the array is the method's inherent purpose - otherwise it would be a surprising side effect and bad practice.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare passing an <code>int</code> vs. passing an array reference to a method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>With an <code>int</code>, the method can't affect the caller's variable; with an array reference, the method gets its own copy of the reference but can still mutate the underlying array the caller can see.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Calling a method causes the flow of control to jump to the start of the method after initializing the parameters. When the method returns, the flow of control returns to the point where the method was called. No code executes in a method after a `return` statement.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the flow of control when a method is called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the parameters are initialized, control jumps to the start of the method body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a method returns?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Flow of control returns to the point in the caller where the method was called.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is executed in a method after a <code>return</code> statement runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing - no code in the method executes after a <code>return</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method has <code>return x;</code> followed by <code>System.out.println("hi");</code>. Does "hi" print?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - the <code>return</code> exits the method immediately, and the compiler will actually flag the <code>println</code> as unreachable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare calling a method to a "jump and come back" operation.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Control jumps into the method body, runs until <code>return</code> (or the end), then comes back to the caller right after the call site.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Values are returned from a method using a `return` statement consisting of the keyword `return` followed by an expression that evaluates to a value of the correct type which is then returned from the method. (In a `void` method `return` is only used with no following expression to return early from a method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you return a value from a non-<code>void</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With a <code>return</code> statement: the keyword <code>return</code> followed by an expression of the correct type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type must the expression after <code>return</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A value of the method's declared return type (or something compatible with it).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>return</code> used in a <code>void</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With no following expression, to exit the method early.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>void</code> method writes <code>return 5;</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - a <code>void</code> method can't return a value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>return</code> in a <code>void</code> method vs. a non-<code>void</code> method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In non-<code>void</code> methods <code>return</code> must be followed by a value of the right type; in <code>void</code> methods <code>return</code> stands alone and is only used to exit early.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The value returned by a method is copied, just like method arguments. Again, this means a reference returned by a method can be used to modify object it references.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is a method's return value passed back to the caller?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is copied, just like method arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method returns a reference, what can the caller do with it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use the reference to modify the object it points to, since both method and caller now hold references to the same object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does "return value is copied" mean the entire object is copied when returning a reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - only the reference (the pointer) is copied; the underlying object is not duplicated.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method returns an internal <code>ArrayList</code>. What's the risk?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller can use the returned reference to modify the list's contents, affecting the object's internal state.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare returning an <code>int</code> vs. returning a reference to a mutable object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Returning an <code>int</code> copies a value the caller can't use to affect the method's data; returning a reference copies a pointer the caller can use to mutate the shared object.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A method call to a non-`void` method is a kind of expression whose value is the value returned by the method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a call to a non-<code>void</code> method, as a language construct?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression whose value is the value returned by the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the value of the expression <code>Math.sqrt(9)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value returned by <code>Math.sqrt</code> - in this case, <code>3.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can you write <code>int x = add(2, 3) + 1;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>add(2, 3)</code> is an expression whose value is the method's return value, so it can be used in arithmetic.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to use a method's result directly as an argument to another method. Can you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - since non-<code>void</code> calls are expressions, you can nest them like <code>foo(bar())</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a non-<code>void</code> method call to a literal like <code>42</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are expressions that have a value; a literal's value is written directly, while a method call's value is whatever the method returns.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A call to a `void` method can only be for effect and not part of an expression since the method doesn't return any value. They typically do not need a `return` statement and simply return when execution reaches the end of the method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't a <code>void</code> method call be used as part of an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it doesn't return any value, so there's nothing to plug into an expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the only reason to call a <code>void</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For its side effects.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do <code>void</code> methods typically need a <code>return</code> statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - they usually just return automatically when execution reaches the end of the method body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When might a <code>void</code> method still use <code>return</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To return early from the method before reaching the end of the body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare what happens at the end of a <code>void</code> method vs. a non-<code>void</code> method with no explicit <code>return</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>void</code> method just returns; a non-<code>void</code> method without a <code>return</code> on some path is a compile error.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Naming methods in method calls</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Within a class, code can reference other methods in the same class simply by their name with the exception that `static` methods cannot call instance methods without an explicit object to invoke the method on. But in non-`static` methods, invoking a method by its simple name is the same as invoking it on `this`, i.e. on the same object the current method was invoked on.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a non-<code>static</code> method, what does calling another method by its simple name (e.g., <code>foo()</code>) implicitly do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It invokes the method on <code>this</code>, the same object the current method was invoked on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't a <code>static</code> method call an instance method using just the instance method's simple name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>static</code> method has no <code>this</code>, so there is no implicit object to invoke the instance method on; an explicit object reference is required.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Within a class, how do you reference another method defined in the same class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Simply by its name, with the caveat that <code>static</code> methods can't call instance methods without an explicit object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a <code>static</code> method tries to call an instance method by its simple name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A compile-time error occurs because there is no implicit <code>this</code> object on which to invoke the instance method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how instance methods and <code>static</code> methods can refer to other methods in the same class.</p></question>
        <answer><p>An instance method can call any other method by simple name (instance calls go through implicit <code>this</code>), but a <code>static</code> method can only call other <code>static</code> methods by simple name; calling instance methods requires an explicit object.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Outside a class, `static` methods are typically referenced using the class name, the dot operator, and the name of the method, e.g. `Math.sqrt(2)` to invoke the `static` `sqrt` method in the class `Math`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you typically invoke a <code>static</code> method from outside its class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using the class name, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code> illustrate about calling <code>static</code> methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>static</code> methods are invoked via the class name (<code>Math</code>) rather than an instance of the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is no object needed to call a <code>static</code> method from outside its class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>static</code> methods belong to the class itself, not to any particular instance, so the class name is enough to locate them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want to call a <code>static</code> method <code>max</code> defined in class <code>Helper</code> from a different class. How do you write the call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Write <code>Helper.max(...)</code>: class name, dot, method name, arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the dot operator play in <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It separates the class name from the <code>static</code> method being invoked on that class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance methods in other classes are invoked on a particular object using an expression that evaluates to a reference to the object, the dot operator, and the name of the method, e.g. `s.substring(1)` to invoke the `substring` method on an instance of `String` referenced by the variable `s`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are instance methods in other classes invoked?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using an expression that evaluates to an object reference, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>s.substring(1)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>s.substring(1)</code>, what does <code>s</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression (here, a variable) that evaluates to a reference to a <code>String</code> object on which <code>substring</code> is invoked.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the key difference between invoking a <code>static</code> method and an instance method from outside its class?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>static</code> methods are invoked via the class name (e.g., <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>), while instance methods are invoked on an object reference (e.g., <code>s.substring(1)</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does the left side of the dot in an instance-method call have to be a variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it can be any expression that evaluates to a reference to an object, such as a method return value or a field access.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you write <code>s.substring(1)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The runtime looks up the object referenced by <code>s</code> and invokes its <code>substring</code> method with argument <code>1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Control constructs</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Control constructs allow us to control the flow of execution other than by calling and returning from methods. They fall into to two kinds: conditional control constructs and and looping control constructs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are control constructs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Language features that control the flow of execution beyond just calling and returning from methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two kinds of control constructs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditional control constructs and looping control constructs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Besides control constructs, what other mechanism affects the flow of execution in a program?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Calling methods and returning from them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do we need control constructs in addition to method calls?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because we need to make decisions and repeat actions within a method, not just transfer control between methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare conditional and looping control constructs at a high level.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditionals choose whether (and which) statements to execute based on a boolean; loops repeat statements zero or more times based on a boolean.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Conditional control constructs</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Conditional statements interrupt the normal sequential flow of control from one statement to the next by allowing some code to execute or not depending on the values of a `boolean` condition.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a conditional statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A statement that interrupts sequential flow by executing code only if a <code>boolean</code> condition has a particular value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "normal" flow of control that conditionals interrupt?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Executing statements sequentially, one after the next, in the order they are written.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines whether a conditional's body runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value of its <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Could a program that never makes decisions be written without conditionals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; conditionals are only needed when some code should run or be skipped depending on a <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of value must a conditional's condition evaluate to in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>boolean</code> value (<code>true</code> or <code>false</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A simple `if` statement affect the flow of control by executing the statements in the `if`'s body only if the `if`'s `boolean` condition evaluates to `true`. This provides a one-way selection where a set of statements either is or is not executed, depending on the condition.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "one-way selection"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A conditional in which a set of statements either executes or is skipped, with no alternative branch — provided by a simple <code>if</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When does a simple <code>if</code>'s body execute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only when the <code>if</code>'s <code>boolean</code> condition evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a simple <code>if</code>'s condition is <code>false</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body is skipped and execution continues with the statement after the <code>if</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a simple <code>if</code> called "one-way"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because there's only one branch — the body — with no alternative block to run when the condition is <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does a simple <code>if</code> differ from an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A simple <code>if</code> has no alternative path; an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> always executes one of two branches.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A two-way selection, written with an `if`/`else`, causes either one set of statements or another to be executed, one when the boolean condition is true and the other when it is false.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a two-way selection?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A conditional that always executes exactly one of two branches depending on a <code>boolean</code> condition, written as <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>, when does the <code>else</code> branch run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When the <code>if</code>'s <code>boolean</code> condition evaluates to <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can both branches of an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> execute in the same run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; exactly one branch runs based on the condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want to print "even" or "odd" based on a number. Which conditional structure fits?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A two-way selection (<code>if</code>/<code>else</code>), since exactly one of the two messages should print.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare one-way and two-way selection.</p></question>
        <answer><p>One-way (simple <code>if</code>) runs its body or does nothing; two-way (<code>if</code>/<code>else</code>) always runs one of two alternative blocks.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A multi-way selection, written with an `if`, one ore more `else if`s, and optionally a final `else`, chooses one of several sets of statements to execute based on a number of different `boolean` conditions. The code that executes is the body of the first `if` or `else if` whose condition is `true` or the body of the `else` if all the conditions are `false`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a multi-way selection?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>if</code> followed by one or more <code>else if</code>s, and optionally a final <code>else</code>, that selects one of several branches based on multiple conditions.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which branch of an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body of the first <code>if</code> or <code>else if</code> whose condition is <code>true</code>; if none are <code>true</code>, the final <code>else</code> runs (if present).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two conditions in an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code> chain are both <code>true</code>, which one's body executes?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only the first one in the chain that evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens in an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain if all conditions are <code>false</code> and there is no final <code>else</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No branch runs; execution just continues after the chain.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare two-way and multi-way selection.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Two-way chooses between exactly two branches; multi-way chooses among many branches, testing conditions in order and running the body of the first one that's <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Any code can go in the body of an `if` or `else` including other `if`, `if`/`else`, and `if`/`else if`/`else` statements, producing nested conditional statements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are nested conditional statements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditional statements (<code>if</code>, <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>, etc.) that appear inside the body of another <code>if</code> or <code>else</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of code can appear inside the body of an <code>if</code> or <code>else</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any code at all, including other conditional statements.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a language-level limit on how deeply you can nest conditionals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; you can nest <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements arbitrarily deeply because any code is allowed inside their bodies.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might you nest conditionals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To make additional decisions only after a prior condition has already selected a branch, expressing more complex decision logic.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does nesting conditionals relate to the rule that "any code" can go in an <code>if</code> body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Since conditional statements are just code, they are allowed in <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> bodies like any other statement, which is exactly what "nesting" means.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Technically `if`/`else if`/`else` statements are just regular `if`/`else` statements with a nested `if`/`else` statement but we write them chained together when we want to express a multi-way selection.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Structurally, what is an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain really?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A regular <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> whose <code>else</code> branch contains another nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statement.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do we write <code>else if</code> as if it were its own construct?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To clearly express a multi-way selection, even though it's really just a nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does Java have a special <code>else if</code> keyword?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; <code>else if</code> is just an <code>else</code> whose body is another <code>if</code> statement, written on the same line by convention.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does chaining <code>else if</code>s help readability compared to deep nesting?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It flattens what would otherwise be increasingly indented nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> blocks into a single visually aligned multi-way selection.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When does writing chained <code>else if</code>s make sense?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you want to express a multi-way selection among several mutually exclusive boolean conditions.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Looping control constructs</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Looping control constructs, also called iteration constructs, change the normal flow of control by repeating a sequence of statements zero or more times.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is another name for looping control constructs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iteration constructs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do loops change the flow of control?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By repeating a sequence of statements zero or more times instead of executing them just once.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a loop's body run zero times?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; if the loop's condition is <code>false</code> on the very first check, the body is never executed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the minimum and maximum number of times a loop body can run in principle?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Zero is the minimum; there is no fixed maximum — it can repeat as long as the condition remains <code>true</code>, potentially forever.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do loops differ from conditionals in how they affect control flow?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditionals run a block at most once based on a condition; loops can run a block many times, re-checking the condition each iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In both `while` and `for` loops, a `boolean` expression is evaluated before each iteration of the loop's body, including the first. When the expression evaluates to `true`, the loop body is executed. Then the loop repeats this process until the `boolean` expression evaluates to false.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop's boolean condition evaluated?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before each iteration, including the first one.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens after a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop executes its body once?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Control returns to the condition; if it's still <code>true</code>, the body runs again, otherwise the loop ends.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the loop condition in a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop checked after the body or before it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the body, each time — including before the very first iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What ends a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its <code>boolean</code> condition evaluating to <code>false</code> when it is checked.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how <code>while</code> and <code>for</code> loops decide whether to run each iteration.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both evaluate a <code>boolean</code> expression before each iteration and run the body only when the expression is <code>true</code>; they differ only in how that expression is set up and updated.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>If the `boolean` expression evaluates to false the first time it is evaluated, the loop body is not executed at all. Conversely, if the `boolean` expression always evaluates to `true`, the loop is an infinite loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a loop's <code>boolean</code> condition is <code>false</code> the first time it's checked?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The loop body never executes at all.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is an infinite loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A loop whose <code>boolean</code> condition always evaluates to <code>true</code>, so the body repeats forever.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>while (false) { ... }</code> were written, how many times would the body run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Zero times, because the condition is <code>false</code> on the first check.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is it possible for a loop body to never run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; if the condition is <code>false</code> the first time it is evaluated, the body is skipped entirely.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a loop that runs zero times with an infinite loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A zero-iteration loop has a condition that's <code>false</code> at its first check; an infinite loop has a condition that's always <code>true</code>, so it never stops.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A `while` loop consists of just two parts: the condition and the body.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two parts of a <code>while</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The condition and the body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many parts does a <code>while</code> loop have, compared to a <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>while</code> loop has just two parts (condition and body); a <code>for</code> loop has three header parts plus a body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the condition play in a <code>while</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's the <code>boolean</code> expression checked before each iteration to decide whether the body runs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a <code>while</code> loop have a built-in initialization or update clause?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it only has a condition and a body, so any initialization or updating must be written separately.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a <code>while</code> loop considered the "simplest" loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it has only two parts — a condition and a body — with no built-in initialization or update mechanism.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A `while` loop executes by evaluating the condition. If the condition is `true` it then executes the body and repeats, back at the condition. Otherwise the loop ends.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Describe the execution cycle of a <code>while</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Evaluate the condition; if <code>true</code>, run the body and go back to evaluate the condition again; if <code>false</code>, end the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a <code>while</code> loop do immediately after executing its body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It jumps back to re-evaluate the condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What causes a <code>while</code> loop to terminate?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its condition evaluating to <code>false</code> when it is checked.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a <code>while</code> loop's condition starts as <code>false</code>, what is the sequence of steps?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Evaluate condition → it's <code>false</code> → loop ends immediately without running the body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare what a <code>while</code> loop does when the condition is <code>true</code> versus <code>false</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>On <code>true</code>, it executes the body and re-checks the condition; on <code>false</code>, it exits the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Both the condition and the body will usually refer to variables defined before the loop. If the condition depends on the values of one or more variables and the body contains code that changes those variables, the condition can eventually become `false` and the loop will stop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where are the variables referenced by a <code>while</code> loop's condition and body usually defined?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the loop itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the body of a <code>while</code> loop usually modify variables that appear in the condition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So the condition can eventually become <code>false</code>, allowing the loop to terminate.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a <code>while</code> loop's body never changes any variable used in the condition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The condition's value never changes, so the loop either runs forever or never runs at all.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the relationship between the condition and body needed for a <code>while</code> loop to stop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body must eventually cause the variables in the condition to take values that make it <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>while</code> loop checks <code>i &lt; 10</code> but the body never changes <code>i</code>. What's the result?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An infinite loop if <code>i</code> starts less than 10, or a zero-iteration loop if <code>i</code> starts at 10 or more.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`while` loops are most useful when you do not know, before the loop starts, exactly how many times it needs to run.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is a <code>while</code> loop most useful?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you don't know ahead of time how many iterations will be needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why prefer a <code>while</code> loop over a <code>for</code> loop for reading input until a sentinel?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you don't know in advance how many inputs there will be, which is exactly what <code>while</code> loops are designed for.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you already know you need exactly 100 iterations, is a <code>while</code> loop the best fit?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Not usually; a <code>for</code> loop is typically a better fit when the number of iterations is known in advance.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give a scenario where a <code>while</code> loop is more natural than a <code>for</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Repeatedly asking the user for input until they type "quit", since the number of prompts isn't known beforehand.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare when to use <code>while</code> versus <code>for</code> loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>while</code> when the number of iterations isn't known in advance; use <code>for</code> when you know how many times to iterate (e.g., over an array).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A `for` loop consists of a header and a body.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two main parts of a <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A header and a body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the header of a <code>for</code> loop appear?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In parentheses right after the <code>for</code> keyword, before the body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the body of a <code>for</code> loop contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The statements to be executed on each iteration of the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a <code>for</code> loop have the same structural parts as a <code>while</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; both have a body, but the <code>for</code> loop also has a structured header containing initialization, condition, and update.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the high-level structure of a <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A header (in parentheses) that controls the loop, followed by a body that runs on each iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The header of a `for` loop consists of three parts, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons: the initialization clause, the condition, and the update clause.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the three parts of a <code>for</code> loop header?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The initialization clause, the condition, and the update clause.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are the three parts of a <code>for</code> loop header separated?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By semicolons, all enclosed in parentheses.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)</code>, which parts correspond to initialization, condition, and update?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int i = 0</code> is initialization, <code>i &lt; 10</code> is the condition, and <code>i++</code> is the update.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does a <code>for</code> loop header use semicolons rather than commas?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because semicolons separate the three distinct clauses (initialization, condition, update) inside the parentheses.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a <code>for</code> loop's header with a <code>while</code> loop's header.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>while</code> loop's header is just a condition; a <code>for</code> loop's header bundles initialization, condition, and update into one place.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The initialization clause is run once, before anything else in the loop. Typically the initialization clause declares and initializes a variable called the loop variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When does the initialization clause of a <code>for</code> loop execute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Exactly once, before anything else in the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the initialization clause typically do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Declares and initializes a loop variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many times does the initialization clause run during the lifetime of a <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once, at the very start of the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "loop variable"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable declared and initialized in a <code>for</code> loop's initialization clause, used to control the loop's iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why put variable initialization inside the <code>for</code> loop header rather than before it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To keep the loop variable scoped to the loop and bundle the loop's control logic in one place.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The condition is evaluated before each iteration of the loop and the loop only continues if it evaluates to `true`. Usually the condition is some expression involving the loop variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is the condition of a <code>for</code> loop evaluated?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before each iteration of the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must the condition evaluate to for the loop to continue?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the condition of a <code>for</code> loop typically involve?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression involving the loop variable, e.g., comparing it to a limit.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)</code>, what does the condition <code>i &lt; n</code> control?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether the loop runs another iteration, checked before each one.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare where the condition is evaluated in a <code>for</code> loop versus a <code>while</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both evaluate the condition before each iteration; the difference is only that the <code>for</code> loop's condition is written inside the loop header alongside initialization and update.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The update clause runs after the body of the loop and just before the next evaluation of the condition. The update clause usually updates the loop variable, typically by incrementing or decrementing it.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When does the update clause of a <code>for</code> loop run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the body runs and just before the next evaluation of the condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the update clause typically do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Updates the loop variable, often by incrementing or decrementing it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does the update clause run before the first iteration's body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it runs only after each body execution, before the next condition check.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)</code>, when does <code>i++</code> execute relative to the body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After each execution of the body and just before <code>i &lt; 10</code> is checked again.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the update clause typically change the loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that the condition can eventually become <code>false</code> and the loop can terminate.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of the `for` loop is executed after the condition is evaluated and before the update clause. Code within the body can refer to the loop variable declared in the loop header.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When does the body of a <code>for</code> loop execute relative to the condition and update clause?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the condition is evaluated (and found <code>true</code>) and before the update clause runs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the body of a <code>for</code> loop refer to the loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; the loop variable declared in the header is in scope inside the body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the order of operations in a single iteration of a <code>for</code> loop (excluding initialization)?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Evaluate condition → if <code>true</code>, execute body → execute update clause → repeat.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful that the body can refer to the loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets the body use the current iteration's value, for example to index into an array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the roles of the body and the update clause in a <code>for</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body does the actual work each iteration; the update clause adjusts the loop variable so the condition can eventually stop the loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`for` loops are typically used when we know, before the loop starts, how many times we want to iterate, e.g. once for every character in a string or element of an array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is a <code>for</code> loop typically preferred?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When the number of iterations is known before the loop starts.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give two common examples where a <code>for</code> loop is appropriate.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iterating once per character in a string and once per element of an array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a <code>for</code> loop a good match for iterating over an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you know the array's length up front, so you know exactly how many times to loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: reading until the user types "quit". Is a <code>for</code> loop the best fit?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the number of iterations isn't known in advance, so a <code>while</code> loop is more natural.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare typical uses of <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for</code> loops suit known-count iteration like array traversal; <code>while</code> loops suit unknown-count iteration that depends on runtime conditions.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A `for` loop can be rewritten into an equivalent `while` loop and vice versa, though the `while` loop will need some code before the loop proper to perform the role of the `for` loop's initialization clause and the update clause will need to appear in the body of the `while` loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can any <code>for</code> loop be rewritten as a <code>while</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> loops are interchangeable in expressive power.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When rewriting a <code>for</code> loop as a <code>while</code> loop, where does the initialization go?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the <code>while</code> loop, as code that runs once before the loop begins.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When rewriting a <code>for</code> loop as a <code>while</code> loop, where does the update clause go?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Inside the body of the <code>while</code> loop, typically at the end so it runs before the next condition check.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> are equivalent, why have both?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>for</code> loops bundle initialization, condition, and update together, making known-count iteration more concise and readable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the structural trade-off between <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for</code> loops centralize loop control in the header; <code>while</code> loops spread it out — initialization before the loop and updates within the body.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The enhanced `for` loop provides a concise way to traverse an array or an `ArrayList` in the common case when we only need to deal with one element at a time and don't care about the index.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the enhanced <code>for</code> loop provide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A concise way to traverse an array or <code>ArrayList</code> when you only need one element at a time and don't care about the index.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop a good choice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you need to process each element of an array or <code>ArrayList</code> in order and don't need its index.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop a poor choice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you need the index of each element, or need to modify the collection's structure during traversal.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of things can you traverse with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop in AP CSA?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an enhanced <code>for</code> loop with a traditional <code>for</code> loop over an array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traditional <code>for</code> loop gives you an index (and thus access to neighbors); an enhanced <code>for</code> loop gives you each element directly but no index.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The enhanced `for` loop consists of a simplified header consisting of just a variable declaration, a colon, and an expression that evaluates to an array or an `ArrayList`, and a body.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the parts of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop header?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable declaration, a colon, and an expression that evaluates to an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What separates the variable declaration from the array expression in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A colon (<code>:</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must the expression to the right of the colon in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array or an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the header of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop with a traditional <code>for</code> loop header.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The enhanced header has just a variable declaration and a collection expression separated by a colon; the traditional header has initialization, condition, and update separated by semicolons.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop header called "simplified"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it has fewer parts than a traditional <code>for</code> header — no explicit initialization, condition, or update.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of an enhanced `for` loop is executed once for each element of the array or `ArrayList` with the variable assigned the value of each element in turn.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How many times does the body of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once for each element of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value does the loop variable take on each iteration of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value of the current element of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In what order does an enhanced <code>for</code> loop visit elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the order of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>, from first element to last.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you need to manually increment any index in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the loop automatically advances through the elements on its own.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how the loop variable is used in a traditional versus enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In a traditional <code>for</code> loop it's typically an index used to access elements; in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop it directly holds each element's value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The loop variable in an enhanced `for` loop is just a regular variable. Assigning a new value to it has no effect on the array itself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of variable is the loop variable in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just a regular local variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you assign a new value to an enhanced <code>for</code> loop's loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only the local variable changes; the underlying array or <code>ArrayList</code> is not modified.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you modify array elements by assigning to the loop variable in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the loop variable is a copy of each element's value, so assigning to it doesn't affect the array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: inside an enhanced <code>for</code> loop <code>for (int x : arr)</code> over an <code>int[] arr</code>, you write <code>x = 0</code> in the loop body. What happens to the array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing; only the local loop variable <code>x</code> changes, and the array is unaffected.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the inability to modify array elements via an enhanced <code>for</code> loop's loop variable affect when you'd choose an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You wouldn't choose it when you need to replace elements of the array; a traditional indexed <code>for</code> loop is required for that.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of a loop can contain any statements including other loops.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of statements can go inside a loop's body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any statements, including other loops.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are nested loops a special language feature or just a consequence of general rules?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A consequence of the general rule that any statement, including a loop, can appear in a loop's body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a limit to how deeply loops can be nested?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No language-level limit — loops can contain other loops arbitrarily deeply.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a loop's body contain conditional statements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; a loop's body can contain any statements, including <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> chains and other loops.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful that loop bodies can contain other loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets you express iteration over multi-dimensional structures like 2D arrays or combinations of elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Nested loops are just loops that appear in the body of another loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are nested loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Loops that appear in the body of another loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a special syntax for nested loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; they're just ordinary loops written inside another loop's body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give a common use case for nested loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iterating over a 2D array, with the outer loop over rows and the inner loop over columns.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a nested loop, which loop is "outer" and which is "inner"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer loop is the one that contains the other; the inner loop is written inside the outer loop's body.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does nesting require the inner and outer loops to be the same kind?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; you can nest any kind of loop inside any other — e.g., a <code>for</code> loop inside a <code>while</code> loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a loop is nested inside another loop, the inner loop must complete before the outer loop can continue.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In nested loops, what must happen before the outer loop continues to its next iteration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The inner loop must run to completion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If the inner loop runs 5 times and the outer loop runs 3 times, how many times does the inner loop's body execute in total?</p></question>
        <answer><p>15 times — 5 inner iterations for each of the 3 outer iterations.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does nesting loops multiply their iteration counts?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the inner loop restarts and completes fully on every single iteration of the outer loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the order of execution in nested loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Outer loop starts an iteration → inner loop runs from start to finish → outer loop advances to its next iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare one iteration of an outer loop with one iteration of an inner loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>One outer iteration corresponds to the inner loop running in its entirety; one inner iteration is just a single pass through the inner body.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Since executing a `return` statement always immediately returns from the current method, it can be used to break out of a loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How can a <code>return</code> statement be used to exit a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By returning from the enclosing method, which immediately stops execution of the loop as a side effect.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the effect of <code>return</code> when executed inside a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It immediately exits not just the loop but the entire enclosing method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can <code>return</code> be used to exit only the innermost of several nested loops while continuing the outer one?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; <code>return</code> exits the entire method, so all enclosing loops stop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can <code>return</code> be used to break out of a loop even though it isn't a loop-specific construct?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because returning from the method abandons whatever code was running, including any loops in progress.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're searching an array for a target and want to stop as soon as you find it. How can <code>return</code> help?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can <code>return</code> the found value (or its index) directly from inside the loop, which immediately ends both the loop and the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>"Off by one" errors occur when the iteration statement loops one time too many or one time too few, for instance for (int i = 0; i &lt;= s.length(); i++) rather than for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++) when iterating over the characters of a string.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an "off by one" error?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A bug where a loop runs one iteration too many or too few.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt;= s.length(); i++)</code> likely buggy when iterating over a string's characters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because valid character indices are <code>0</code> to <code>s.length() - 1</code>; using <code>&lt;=</code> lets <code>i</code> reach <code>s.length()</code>, which is out of bounds.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the correct loop condition for iterating over every character of a string by index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>i &lt; s.length()</code>, starting from <code>i = 0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>An off-by-one error can cause either too few or too many iterations — what's a symptom of each?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Too few: the last element is skipped. Too many: an extra iteration runs, often triggering an index-out-of-bounds error.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the choice between <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code> in a loop condition relate to off-by-one errors?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Switching between them changes the number of iterations by exactly one, which is where off-by-one bugs often come from.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Unintended infinite loops occur when the condition never becomes false, often due to a bug in the update code.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What causes an unintended infinite loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A loop whose condition never becomes <code>false</code>, often because of a bug in the code that should be updating the variables it depends on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where do unintended infinite loops usually originate?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the update code — either it's missing, wrong, or not affecting the variables used in the condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>while (i &lt; 10)</code> loop that forgets to change <code>i</code> in the body. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If <code>i</code> starts below 10, it's an unintended infinite loop because the condition never becomes <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you avoid unintended infinite loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Make sure each iteration makes progress toward the condition becoming <code>false</code> by correctly updating the variables it depends on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an intentional infinite loop with an unintended one.</p></question>
        <answer><p>An intentional infinite loop is written knowingly (e.g., for a server loop), while an unintended one is a bug — typically caused by faulty update logic.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Arrays</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arrays are a reference type that collects multiple values of a given type into a single value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type that collects multiple values of a given type into a single value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is an array a primitive type or a reference type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a single array hold values of different types (e.g. an <code>int</code> and a <code>String</code>)?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. An array collects multiple values of a given (single) type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does an array differ from a single variable of a primitive type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A single variable holds one value, while an array bundles multiple values of the same type into one reference value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want one value that contains 20 <code>double</code>s. What kind of thing do you need?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array of <code>double</code>, which is a reference type collecting all 20 values into a single value.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The values in an array are called the elements of the array or sometimes the components.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the values inside an array called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The elements (or sometimes the components) of the array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is "component" a valid synonym for "element" when talking about arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, the values in an array are sometimes called components.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone says "the third component of the array", what are they referring to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The third value (element) stored in the array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Fill in the blank: the values in an array are called its ___.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Elements (or components).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare: "element" vs. "component" of an array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They refer to the same thing — the individual values stored in the array.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Array elements can be either primitive or reference values.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of values can array elements be?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Either primitive values or reference values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you have an array of <code>String</code> objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Array elements can be reference values, including <code>String</code> references.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an array hold <code>int</code> values directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Array elements can be primitive values like <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you have an array of arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer array's elements are reference values pointing to other array objects — this is allowed because elements can be references.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an array of <code>int</code> with an array of <code>Integer</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first stores primitive <code>int</code> values directly; the second stores references to <code>Integer</code> objects. Both are allowed because array elements can be primitive or reference values.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The size of an array is established at the time of its creation and cannot be changed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is the size of an array determined?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the time the array is created.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you grow an existing array to hold more elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Once created, an array's size cannot be changed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you need more room than the array currently has?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You must create a new, larger array and copy elements over — the original array's size cannot be changed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: You create <code>new int[5]</code> and later want it to hold 10 values. What are your options?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Create a new array of size 10 and copy values from the old one. You cannot resize the original.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare array size with <code>ArrayList</code> size.</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array's size is fixed at creation and cannot change; an <code>ArrayList</code> can grow and shrink as elements are added or removed.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When an array is created using the keyword `new` and a size (e.g. `new int[10]`) all of its elements are initialized with the standard zero value for the element type: 0 for `int`s, `0.0` for `double`s, `false` for `boolean`s, and `null` for all reference types.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What value do the elements of <code>new int[10]</code> start out as?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All 0.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default initial value of each element in <code>new double[5]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0.0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does each element of <code>new boolean[3]</code> contain right after creation?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the initial values of elements in <code>new String[4]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All <code>null</code>, since <code>String</code> is a reference type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the initial element values of <code>new int[3]</code> vs. <code>new Integer[3]</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>new int[3]</code> starts with three <code>0</code>s (primitive zero); <code>new Integer[3]</code> starts with three <code>null</code>s (reference default).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Initializer lists can be used to create arrays containing specific values, e.g. `new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }`. Arrays created this way have their length set to the number of elements provided.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an array initializer list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A syntax like <code>new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }</code> that creates an array already filled with the specific values listed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the length of the array created by <code>new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>3 — the length equals the number of elements provided.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How else can you create an array besides using <code>new Type[size]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With an initializer list, e.g. <code>new int[] { 1, 2, 3 }</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the length when you use <code>new String[] { "a", "b", "c", "d" }</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The array's length is set to 4, the number of elements in the initializer list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>new int[3]</code> and <code>new int[] { 0, 0, 0 }</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both create a 3-element <code>int</code> array with all zeros. The first relies on default initialization; the second uses an explicit initializer list.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arrays have a read-only instance variable `length` which gives the number of elements in the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you find the number of elements in an array <code>xs</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>xs.length</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>length</code> on an array a method or a field?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An instance variable (field), so you write <code>xs.length</code>, not <code>xs.length()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you assign to <code>xs.length</code> to resize an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>length</code> is read-only.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you write <code>xs.length = 5;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A compile error, because <code>length</code> is a read-only instance variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare getting the size of an array vs. a <code>String</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For an array you use the field <code>xs.length</code>; for a <code>String</code> you call the method <code>s.length()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The elements of an array are accessed using square brackets ([]) and an index, e.g. `xs[0]` accesses the 0th element of the array `xs`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What syntax is used to access an element of an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Square brackets with an index, e.g. <code>xs[0]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>xs[0]</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The 0th (first) element of the array <code>xs</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are array indexes in Java 0-based or 1-based?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0-based — the first element is at index 0.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How would you access the element right after <code>xs[0]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using <code>xs[1]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>xs[0]</code> and <code>xs.length</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>xs[0]</code> uses an index in square brackets to read an element; <code>xs.length</code> reads the read-only field that stores the array's size.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The valid indexes for an array are 0 through length - 1, inclusive.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the valid indexes for an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0 through <code>length - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For an array of length 10, what is the largest valid index?</p></question>
        <answer><p>9, since valid indexes go from 0 to <code>length - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the smallest valid index for any array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>An array <code>xs</code> has length 5. Is <code>xs[5]</code> valid?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. The valid indexes are 0 through 4 (length - 1).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the range of valid indexes for arrays of length 1 vs. length 100.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Length 1: only index 0 is valid. Length 100: indexes 0 through 99 are valid. In both cases the range is 0 to <code>length - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Using an invalid index (less than 0 or greater than length - 1) will cause an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you use an out-of-range array index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which indexes count as "invalid" for an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any index less than 0 or greater than <code>length - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens at runtime if you access <code>xs[-1]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a loop iterates up to <code>xs.length</code> (inclusive) and reads <code>xs[i]</code>. What goes wrong?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the last iteration <code>i == xs.length</code>, which is past the last valid index, so an <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a compile-time error with the error from using <code>xs[xs.length]</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>xs[xs.length]</code> compiles fine but throws an <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> at runtime — it's a runtime error, not a compile-time error.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An array access expression is like a variable in that it can be used to obtain a value or as a place that can be assigned a value with = or any applicable compound assignment operator (e.g. `+=` or `++` on on an array of numbers).</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In what two ways can an array access expression like <code>xs[i]</code> be used?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As a value to read, or as a place to assign a value (the left side of <code>=</code> or a compound assignment).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>xs[3] = 7;</code> legal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. An array access can appear on the left side of an assignment, just like a variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>xs[i]++</code> on an array of <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element at index <code>i</code> is incremented by 1, because array accesses support compound assignment and increment operators.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to add 5 to <code>xs[2]</code>. Write a compound assignment.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>xs[2] += 5;</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how a regular variable and an array access expression are used.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can be read to obtain a value and both can be assigned to with <code>=</code> or compound operators like <code>+=</code> and <code>++</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Looping over the individual elements of an array is also called traversing the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "traversing" an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Looping over the individual elements of the array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What word describes the process of visiting each element of an array one by one?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method uses a <code>for</code> loop to examine every element of an array, what is it doing to the array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to print every element of <code>xs</code>. What general operation are you performing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traversal of the array <code>xs</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "looping over an array" with "traversing an array".</p></question>
        <answer><p>They mean the same thing — traversing is just the formal name for looping over each element of an array.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Traversing an array with a standard `for` or `while` loop requires using an index to access each element of the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When you traverse an array with a standard <code>for</code> or <code>while</code> loop, how do you get at each element?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You use an index variable and access elements with <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does a standard <code>for</code> or <code>while</code> loop need an index when traversing an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because these loops don't automatically pull out each element — you must use an index to access <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; xs.length; i++)</code>, what is <code>i</code> used for?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As the index to access each element of the array, e.g. <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're writing a <code>while</code> loop to sum an array. What variable must you maintain besides the running sum?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An index variable so you can access each element as <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a standard <code>for</code> loop traversal with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop traversal.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A standard <code>for</code> loop uses an index to access <code>xs[i]</code>; an enhanced <code>for</code> loop gives you each element directly without an index.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>2d arrays</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays. Therefore, the way 2d arrays are created and indexed is similar to 1d array objects.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are 2d arrays actually stored in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As arrays of arrays.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is creating and indexing a 2d array similar to a 1d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because a 2d array is really just a 1d array whose elements happen to be 1d arrays.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If 2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays, what is the type of a single "row" of an <code>int[][]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int[]</code> — a 1d array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you have <code>int[][] grid</code>. What does <code>grid[0]</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first inner array (row), which is itself a 1d array of <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a 2d array and a 1d array structurally.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A 2d array is a 1d array whose elements are themselves 1d arrays, so operations on it resemble 1d-array operations applied at two levels.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>It is equally correct to think of a 2d array as a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is another accurate way to describe a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is it wrong to describe a 2d array as a "1d array of arrays"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. That's an equally correct way to think about it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you view a 2d array as a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays, what does that imply about its element type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each element of the outer array is itself an array — the element type is an array type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to swap two rows of a 2d array. How does thinking of the 2d array as a 1d array whose elements are arrays help?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Since the outer array's elements are just array references, swapping two rows is the same as swapping two elements of a 1d array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "2d array" with "1d array of 1d arrays".</p></question>
        <answer><p>They describe the same structure — a 2d array is literally implemented as a 1d array whose elements are 1d arrays.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The square brackets `[row][col]` are used to access and modify an element in a 2d array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What syntax accesses a single element in a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Two sets of square brackets: <code>arr[row][col]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you set element at row 2, column 3 of <code>grid</code> to 7?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>grid[2][3] = 7;</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the first pair of brackets select in <code>arr[row][col]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The row — the inner 1d array stored at index <code>row</code> of the outer array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to read the top-left corner of a 2d array <code>arr</code>. What expression do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>arr[0][0]</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare accessing an element of a 1d array vs. a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>1d uses one index in brackets (<code>xs[i]</code>); 2d uses two (<code>arr[row][col]</code>), one for the outer array and one for the inner.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>2d arrays can be initialized with specific values by writing a nested initialization expression like `{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you initialize a 2d array with specific values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With a nested initializer expression, e.g. <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does each inner <code>{ ... }</code> in <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A single row (a 1d inner array) of the 2d array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many rows and columns does the array from <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code> have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>2 rows and 3 columns.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a 2d array representing a 2x2 identity matrix of <code>int</code>. Write an initializer.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>{ { 1, 0 }, { 0, 1 } }</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare initializer lists for 1d and 2d arrays.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A 1d initializer is a single list like <code>{ 1, 2, 3 }</code>; a 2d initializer nests lists, with each inner list being a row: <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>2d arrays are typically traversed using nested loops.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are 2d arrays typically traversed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With nested loops.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do you need more than one loop to traverse a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you need to visit each element in each row — one loop iterates rows and the other iterates within each row.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you use only a single loop over a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You visit only the rows (inner arrays), not the individual elements inside each row.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: print every element of a 2d <code>int</code> array. What loop structure do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A nested loop — an outer loop over the rows and an inner loop over the columns of each row.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare traversing a 1d array with traversing a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A 1d traversal needs one loop; a 2d traversal typically uses nested loops, one for the outer array and one for each inner array.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Since 2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays, the outer loop iterates over the array whose elements are 1d arrays and the inner loop iterates over the elements of the 1d array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In a nested 2d-array traversal, what does the outer loop iterate over?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer array, whose elements are 1d arrays (rows).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the inner loop iterate over when traversing a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The elements of the current 1d inner array (the row selected by the outer loop).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the nested-loop structure used to traverse a 2d array mirror its "array of arrays" storage?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each level of the nested loop matches one level of the nested structure: the outer loop walks the outer array, the inner loop walks an inner array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: given <code>int[][] arr</code>, what is a natural meaning for the outer-loop variable and inner-loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer-loop variable picks a row (a 1d <code>int[]</code>), and the inner-loop variable picks a column index within that row.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare what each level of a nested loop "sees" in a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer loop sees rows (1d arrays); the inner loop sees the individual elements within a single row.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In the outer loop of nested enhanced `for` loops used to traverse a 2d array, the type of the loop variable must be the type of each row, i.e. a 1d array. In the inner loop, the type of the loop variable is the actual element type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In a nested enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>int[][]</code>, what type is the outer loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int[]</code> — the type of each row.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In the same nested enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>int[][]</code>, what type is the inner loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> — the element type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why must the outer enhanced-<code>for</code> variable be a 1d array type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the 2d array's elements are themselves 1d arrays, so that's what you get on each iteration of the outer loop.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: write the headers of a nested enhanced <code>for</code> over <code>double[][] table</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for (double[] row : table) { for (double v : row) { ... } }</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare outer vs. inner loop variable types in a nested enhanced <code>for</code> over a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer variable has the row type (a 1d array); the inner variable has the element type of that row.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Typically, and always on the AP exam, 2d arrays are arranged with the outer array holding 1d arrays representing the rows of the 2d array. Thus to access the element at row `r` and column `c`, we use `arr[r][c]`. This form is called "row-major order".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "row-major order" for 2d arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An arrangement where the outer array holds 1d arrays that represent rows, so element at row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code> is <code>arr[r][c]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>On the AP exam, how are 2d arrays always arranged?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In row-major order: the outer array holds rows, so <code>arr[r][c]</code> accesses row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In row-major order, what does the first index of <code>arr[r][c]</code> select?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The row.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: in row-major order, how do you access the element in the 3rd row and 5th column?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>arr[2][4]</code> — remembering that indexes are 0-based.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the meaning of the two indexes in row-major order.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first index is the row number and the second is the column number within that row.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>It is, however, possible to think of a 2d array as representing an array of columns in which case to get the element at row `r` and column `c` you would write `arr[c][r]`. This is called "column-major order".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "column-major order" for a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Treating the outer array as holding columns instead of rows, so the element at row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code> is <code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In column-major order, how do you access the element at row <code>r</code> and column <code>c</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the outer array represent in column-major order?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The columns of the 2d array.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: if a 2d array <code>arr</code> is being used in column-major order, what does <code>arr[0]</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first column of the 2d array (as a 1d array of its entries).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare row-major and column-major order.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In row-major order the outer array holds rows and you write <code>arr[r][c]</code>; in column-major order the outer array holds columns and you write <code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All algorithms that work with 1d arrays will work with 2d arrays, as long as they apply to arrays whose elements are arrays.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why do 1d-array algorithms also work on 2d arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because a 2d array is just a 1d array whose elements are arrays, so any 1d-array algorithm applies — it just operates on elements that happen to be arrays.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What condition must a 1d-array algorithm meet to work on a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It must apply to arrays whose elements are themselves arrays.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you apply a 1d-array "find the max element" algorithm to a 2d <code>int</code> array without adjustment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It treats each row (a 1d array reference) as an element, which isn't meaningful for finding a max <code>int</code>; you'd need to apply the algorithm at the inner level too.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to reverse the order of rows in a 2d array. Can you reuse a 1d-array reverse algorithm?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. A 1d-array reverse applied to the outer array swaps its elements (the row references), effectively reversing the rows.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare applying a 1d algorithm to a 1d array vs. the outer level of a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>On a 1d array it manipulates individual values; on the outer level of a 2d array it manipulates entire rows (1d arrays), because those are the outer array's elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</content>
</invoke>
  <section>
    <title>Classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A class defines a common structure for many objects. The structure is made up of variables, constructors, and methods which, collectively, are called the "members" of a class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a class define?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A common structure for many objects, made up of variables, constructors, and methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the "members" of a class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The variables, constructors, and methods of the class, collectively.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two objects are instances of the same class, what do they share?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They share the same structure: the same set of variables, constructors, and methods defined by the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write a new class in a Java program?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You define a template that specifies what variables, constructors, and methods any object of that class will have.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a class to its instances.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A class is a blueprint defining structure (members); instances are actual objects created from that blueprint.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Defining a class also defines a new type that can be used anywhere a type is needed: in variable declarations, as the return type of a method, or as the type of element on an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What else does defining a class create besides a template for objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new type that can be used anywhere a type is needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name three places you can use a class as a type.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In variable declarations, as a method return type, and as the element type of an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>Point p;</code> after defining a <code>Point</code> class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You declare a variable whose type is the new <code>Point</code> type introduced by the class definition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a method to return a <code>Student</code>. What must exist first?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>Student</code> class must be defined, which also defines <code>Student</code> as a type usable as a return type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a user-defined class type similar to a primitive type like <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can be used anywhere a type is needed: in variable declarations, method return types, parameters, and array element types.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An object is a single instance of a class whose data lives somewhere in memory distinct from all other objects.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A single instance of a class whose data lives in memory distinct from all other objects.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two objects are the same class, do they share the same memory for their data?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, each object's data lives in its own distinct location in memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens in memory when you create a new object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A distinct region of memory is allocated to hold that object's data, separate from all other objects.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "class" and "object" as concepts.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A class is a definition of structure; an object is a concrete instance of that class with its own data in memory.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can two <code>Point</code> objects hold different x and y values at the same time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each object has its own distinct memory storing its own copy of the instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title><code>static</code> members</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Variables and methods can be either static, marked with the `static` keyword, or non-static, without that keyword. Non-static members are also known as "instance variables" and "instance methods".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What keyword marks a member as static?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>static</code> keyword.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are non-static members also called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables and instance methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method declaration does not have the <code>static</code> keyword, what kind of method is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An instance method (non-static).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you see <code>private int count;</code> in a class. Static or instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variable, because there is no <code>static</code> keyword.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare static and instance members by how they are declared.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static members include the <code>static</code> keyword in their declaration; instance members do not.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Static variables and methods can be marked as either `public` or `private` and then marked with the `static` keyword before the variable type or the return type of a method, e.g. `public static int`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does <code>static</code> go relative to <code>public</code> or <code>private</code> and the type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the access modifier and before the variable type or return type, e.g. <code>public static int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a static method be marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Static members can be either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the declaration <code>public static int count</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It declares a public static variable named <code>count</code> of type <code>int</code> that belongs to the class itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to declare a private static <code>double</code> method named <code>rate()</code>. How do you start the declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private static double rate()</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the syntax for declaring a static field vs. an instance field.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They look the same except the static field includes the <code>static</code> keyword between the access modifier and the type.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each static variable represents a single value stored in the class itself and shared by all instances of the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where is a static variable's value stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the class itself, not in any particular instance.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you create 10 instances of a class with a static variable, how many copies of that variable exist?</p></question>
        <answer><p>One, shared by all instances.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when one instance changes a static variable's value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All instances see the change, because they all share the same single value stored in the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want every <code>Counter</code> object to share a running total. Static or instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static, so all instances share one value stored in the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare static variables to instance variables in terms of storage.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each instance variable has its own per-object value; a static variable has one value stored in the class and shared by all instances.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Static methods can only access static variables and call other static methods.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What can a static method directly access?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only static variables and other static methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't a static method directly use an instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because a static method is not tied to any particular instance, so there is no specific object whose instance variable it would access.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to reference an instance variable directly from inside a static method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The code won't compile, because a static method has no implicit instance to access the variable from.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a static method needs to call another method in the same class. What must be true of that other method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It must also be static (to be called directly without an instance).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare static and instance methods in terms of what they can access.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance methods can access both static and instance members; static methods can only directly access static members.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Static members are typically accessed with the class name and the dot operator, e.g. `Math.PI` and `Math.abs()`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are static members typically accessed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using the class name and the dot operator, e.g. <code>Math.PI</code> or <code>Math.abs()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.PI</code> access?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A static variable named <code>PI</code> defined in the <code>Math</code> class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you write <code>Math.abs(-5)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You call the static <code>abs</code> method on the <code>Math</code> class itself, not on any instance.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class <code>Counter</code> has a static method <code>reset()</code>. How do you call it from another class?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Counter.reset();</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the typical way of calling static vs. instance methods.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static methods are called on the class name (<code>Math.abs()</code>); instance methods are called on an object reference (<code>p.getX()</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Instance variables</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>An object's state is stored in its instance variables and each object has its own values its instance variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where is an object's state stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In its instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do two different objects of the same class share instance variable values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, each object has its own values for its instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you change one object's instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only that object's state changes; other objects of the same class are unaffected.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>Point p1</code> has x=3 and <code>Point p2</code> has x=7. Why can they differ?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>x</code> is an instance variable, so each <code>Point</code> object has its own copy.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "state" and "instance variables".</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables are the storage; the state of an object is the collective values currently held in those variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance variables create a "has-a" relationship between the object and the values stored in its instance variables, as in a `Point` has an x and y value. (This is often contrasted to the "is-a" relationship created when one class `extends` another.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of relationship do instance variables create?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A "has-a" relationship between the object and the values stored in its instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is an example of a "has-a" relationship?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>Point</code> has an x value and a y value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is an "is-a" relationship?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The relationship created when one class <code>extends</code> another (inheritance).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Car</code> class has an <code>Engine</code> instance variable. What kind of relationship is this?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A "has-a" relationship: a <code>Car</code> has an <code>Engine</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "has-a" and "is-a" relationships.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Has-a" comes from instance variables (composition); "is-a" comes from one class <code>extends</code>ing another (inheritance).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance variables can be marked as either `public` or `private` before the variable type, e.g `private int n`. Typically they are made `private`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What access modifiers can be applied to instance variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are instance variables typically public or private?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Typically <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the access modifier go in a declaration like <code>private int n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the variable type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to prevent code outside the class from directly reading or writing a field. How do you declare it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Mark it <code>private</code>, e.g. <code>private int n;</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do programmers usually prefer <code>private</code> instance variables to <code>public</code> ones?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To hide implementation details and protect the object's state from being changed directly by outside code.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Constructors</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors are invoked to create objects. A constructor's signature consists of the constructor name, which always matches the class name, and a parameter list.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a constructor's signature consist of?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The constructor name (which always matches the class name) and a parameter list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must a constructor's name always match?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a constructor is invoked?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new object is created.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class is named <code>Point</code>. What must its constructors be named?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Point</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a constructor's signature to a regular method's signature.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both have a name and a parameter list, but a constructor's name must match the class name and it has no return type.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Every object is created by calling a constructor using the keyword `new` followed by the class name and an argument list that corresponds to one of the class's constructors.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What keyword is used to create a new object?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>new</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What follows the <code>new</code> keyword in an object creation expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class name and an argument list matching one of the class's constructors.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>new Point(3, 4)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java creates a new <code>Point</code> object by calling the <code>Point</code> constructor that takes two arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class <code>Dog</code> has a constructor <code>Dog(String name)</code>. How do you create a new <code>Dog</code> named "Rex"?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>new Dog("Rex")</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does Java know which constructor to call when you use <code>new</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It matches the argument list to one of the class's constructors by the number and types of arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The job of a constructor is to initialize the state of an object and leave it in a usable state. Often constructors assign the values passed as arguments to the constructor to the object's instance variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the job of a constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To initialize the state of a new object and leave it in a usable state.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do constructors often do with their arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Assign the argument values to the object's instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a constructor fails to initialize an object's state?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object may be left in an unusable or invalid state.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Point</code> constructor takes <code>int x</code> and <code>int y</code>. What should it typically do inside the body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Assign <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> to the corresponding instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a constructor's job to a regular method's job.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A regular method performs behavior on an existing object; a constructor's job is specifically to initialize a new object's state so it is usable.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors have parameter lists that work just like method parameter lists, defining local variables that are initialized with the values of the arguments passed to a call to the constructor. The arguments should provide the data needed to initialize the object's state.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do constructor parameter lists compare to method parameter lists?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They work the same way: each parameter is a local variable initialized with the value of the corresponding argument.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What should the arguments passed to a constructor provide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The data needed to initialize the object's state.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to constructor parameters when the constructor is called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are created as local variables and initialized with the argument values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a <code>Circle</code> constructor that sets the radius. What should its parameter list include?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A parameter for the radius, e.g. <code>Circle(double radius)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are constructor parameters visible outside the constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, they are local variables scoped to the constructor body, just like method parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When no constructor is written, Java provides a no-argument constructor and all instance variables are set to the default value for their type. (0 for int, 0.0 for double, false for boolean, and null for all reference types.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does Java do if you don't write any constructors?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It provides a no-argument constructor that sets all instance variables to their type's default value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of an <code>int</code> instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of a <code>boolean</code> instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of a reference type instance variable like <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>null</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write a class with no constructors and one <code>double</code> field. What value does that field have right after <code>new</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a mutable object is passed as an argument to a constructor and stored in an instance variable, any mutations made to that object by code in the class will change the state for all code that has a reference to that object. Sometimes it's necessary to instead store a copy of the argument to avoid changing the original object out from under other code. Other times that's the whole point of being passed the object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a mutable object is passed to a constructor and stored in an instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class and the caller share a reference to the same object, so mutations by either side are visible to both.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might a constructor store a copy of a mutable argument instead of the argument itself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To avoid the class mutating the original object from under other code that holds a reference to it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When might sharing the same mutable object between caller and class actually be desired?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When the whole point is for both sides to see changes made through the shared reference.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: your class stores an <code>ArrayList</code> passed into its constructor. Later the caller adds items to that list. What does the class see?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class sees the added items, because both hold the same reference to one list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare storing a reference directly vs. storing a copy of a mutable argument.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Storing the reference shares state and mutations between caller and class; storing a copy isolates them so each has independent state.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Methods in classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>An object's behavior—what we can do with the object—is defined by the methods in its class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What defines an object's behavior?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The methods defined in its class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "behavior" mean in the context of objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What you can do with the object, as defined by its class's methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two classes have different methods, what differs between their objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Their behavior—what can be done with those objects.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>BankAccount</code> class defines <code>deposit</code> and <code>withdraw</code>. What does that tell you about <code>BankAccount</code> objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Their behavior includes the ability to have money deposited into and withdrawn from them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "state" and "behavior" of an object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>State is stored in instance variables; behavior is defined by the methods in the object's class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance methods are called on objects of the class while `static` methods are called on the class itself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are instance methods called on?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Objects of the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are static methods called on?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you try to call an instance method without an object reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It won't compile—instance methods require an object to be called on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you see <code>p.distance(q)</code>. Is <code>distance</code> static or instance?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance, because it is called on the object <code>p</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how you invoke static vs. instance methods.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static methods: <code>ClassName.method()</code>. Instance methods: <code>object.method()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance methods have access to all an object's instance variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do instance methods have access to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All of the object's instance variables.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an instance method read a <code>private</code> instance variable of its own object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—instance methods have access to all of the object's instance variables regardless of access modifier.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when an instance method refers to an instance variable by name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It accesses that variable on the object the method was called on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: an instance method of <code>Point</code> needs to use <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>. Can it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because instance methods have access to all instance variables of the object they are called on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare instance and static methods in terms of access to instance variables.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance methods have direct access to the object's instance variables; static methods do not (they have no implicit object).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods that take no arguments and simply return the value of an instance variable are called "getters" or, more formally, "accessors". They are used to give code outside the class access to the object's state without making instance variables public.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "getter"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method that takes no arguments and returns the value of an instance variable. Also called an "accessor".</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why use getters instead of making instance variables public?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To give outside code read access to state without exposing the instance variables directly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the more formal name for a getter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An accessor.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>Point</code> has a <code>private int x</code>. How would you typically expose its value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Define a getter like <code>public int getX() { return x; }</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare making a field public vs. providing a getter.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A public field lets outside code both read and write it directly; a getter lets outside code only read, while keeping the field private.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods that return `void`, take a single argument, and assign it to the value of an instance variable are called "setters". More generally, methods that change any part of an object's state are called "mutators".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "setter"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method that returns <code>void</code>, takes a single argument, and assigns it to an instance variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "mutator"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>More generally, any method that changes some part of an object's state.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is every mutator a setter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Every setter is a mutator, but mutators include any method that changes state, not just simple single-argument assignments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method <code>deposit(double amount)</code> adds to a balance field. Setter, mutator, or both?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A mutator (it changes state), but not a simple setter, because it doesn't just assign the argument to a field.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare setters and mutators.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Setters are a specific kind of mutator: <code>void</code>, one argument, assigned to an instance variable. Mutators are any methods that change state.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Access modifiers</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The keywords `public` and `private` control what code can access class members.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do the keywords <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They control what code can access class members.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> applied to classes or to members?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can be applied to members; <code>public</code> can also be applied to top-level classes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to code that tries to access a member it isn't allowed to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It won't compile.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to restrict who can call a helper method. Which keyword do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> conceptually.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are access modifiers that define boundaries: <code>public</code> opens a member to all code; <code>private</code> restricts it to the declaring class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The keyword `private` restricts access to only code within the declaring class, while the keyword `public` allows access from any code.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What code can access a <code>private</code> member?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only code within the declaring class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What code can access a <code>public</code> member?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any code.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when code outside the class tries to use a <code>private</code> field?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It fails to compile.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: class <code>A</code> has a private method. Can class <code>B</code> call it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, only code within class <code>A</code> can call it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the access scope of <code>public</code> vs. <code>private</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>: accessible from anywhere. <code>private</code>: accessible only from within the declaring class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Classes cannot be marked `private` and are typically marked `public`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can a top-level class be marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are top-level classes typically marked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to write <code>private class Foo { }</code> at the top level?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It won't compile; top-level classes cannot be <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a class to be usable from any other class. Which modifier do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare access modifier options for members vs. top-level classes.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Members can be <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>; top-level classes can be <code>public</code> but not <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Access to variables should usually be kept internal to the class. Therefore, instance variables are usually made `private`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are instance variables usually marked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are instance variables usually made <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because access to variables should usually be kept internal to the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to a design that makes all instance variables <code>public</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It loses the benefit of keeping variable access internal to the class, letting outside code read and modify state directly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're writing a new class and are about to declare an instance variable. Default choice for modifier?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare designs with public vs. private instance variables.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Public variables expose internal state to outside code; private variables keep state internal and force outside access to go through methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors are typically made `public` but sometimes classes will have `private` constructors that are only used within the class, either from other constructors or from methods that construct new instances of the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are constructors typically marked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When might a constructor be marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When it is only meant to be used within the class, from other constructors or from methods that construct new instances.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What can call a <code>private</code> constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only code within the same class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class wants to control how its instances are created, providing only static factory methods. Useful modifier for its constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>, so outside code cannot call it directly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare typical usage of <code>public</code> vs. <code>private</code> constructors.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Public constructors let any code create instances; private constructors restrict instance creation to code inside the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods are equally likely to be `public` or `private`. The `public` methods define what we can do with instances of a class but `private` methods are useful for breaking up big methods into sub-methods that are only useful within a class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do <code>public</code> methods define?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What outside code can do with instances of a class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why write <code>private</code> methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To break up big methods into smaller sub-methods that are only useful within the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are methods more commonly public or private?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are about equally common; each has its typical role.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you extract a helper used only by one method inside a class. What modifier should the helper usually have?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the roles of public and private methods.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Public methods form the class's external interface; private methods are internal helpers used to organize the class's own code.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Code within a class can access the `private` variables and methods of any instance of the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Whose <code>private</code> members can code inside a class access?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The private members of any instance of that class, not just <code>this</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a method of <code>Point</code> access a private field of a different <code>Point</code> object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—code within a class can access private members of any instance of the same class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a method compares <code>this.x</code> to <code>other.x</code> where both are <code>Point</code> objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It works, even if <code>x</code> is private, because the access rule is per-class, not per-object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: writing an <code>equals</code> method for <code>Point</code> that reads another <code>Point</code>'s private fields. Allowed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because both objects are of the same class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "private per object" with Java's actual rule.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java's rule is per class, not per object: any code in a class can see any instance of that class's private members.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Encapsulation</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Encapsulation is a technique in which implementation details of a class are kept hidden from code outside the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is encapsulation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A technique in which implementation details of a class are kept hidden from code outside the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does encapsulation hide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Implementation details of a class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a class is well-encapsulated and you change its internal implementation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Outside code is unaffected because it doesn't depend on the hidden details.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class exposes only a few public methods and keeps its fields private. Is this good encapsulation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—it hides implementation details behind a small public interface.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare encapsulated and non-encapsulated designs.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Encapsulated designs hide implementation behind a public interface; non-encapsulated designs expose internals, letting outside code depend on them.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When designing a class, programmers make decisions about what parts of its state to make accessible and modifiable from an external class. Data can be either accessible, modifiable, both, or neither.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What four combinations of accessibility and modifiability can a piece of state have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Accessible only, modifiable only, both accessible and modifiable, or neither.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What decision are programmers making when they design a class's interface?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Which parts of the object's state external code should be able to read and/or modify.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "accessible but not modifiable" look like in practice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A getter with no corresponding setter—outside code can read the value but not change it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a piece of state has neither a getter nor a setter. What's its external visibility?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Neither accessible nor modifiable from outside the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "accessible" and "modifiable" as separate design choices.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Accessibility means outside code can read a piece of state; modifiability means outside code can change it. Each can be granted or denied independently.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>State can be encapsulated by storing it in `private` instance variables and access controlled by what getter, setter, and other mutator methods are provided.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is state typically encapsulated in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By storing it in <code>private</code> instance variables and exposing only the getters, setters, or other mutators you choose.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What controls how outside code can access encapsulated state?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The set of getter, setter, and mutator methods provided by the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a <code>private</code> field has a getter but no setter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Outside code can read the value but cannot change it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want an immutable-looking <code>Point</code> where outside code can read <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> but not change them. How do you design it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Make <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> private, provide <code>getX</code> and <code>getY</code>, and provide no setters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a class with only getters to one with getters and setters.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only getters: read-only state from outside. Getters plus setters: state is both readable and writable from outside.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title><code>toString</code></title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `toString` method is inherited from `java.lang.Object` and is frequently overridden to provide a concise, human-readable representation of an object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the <code>toString</code> method come from?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is inherited from <code>java.lang.Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>toString</code> frequently overridden?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To provide a concise, human-readable representation of an object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you don't override <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The inherited <code>Object.toString</code> is used, which is usually not human-readable (class name plus hash).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want <code>Point</code> objects to print as "(3, 4)". What should you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Override <code>toString</code> in the <code>Point</code> class to return a string like <code>"(" + x + ", " + y + ")"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the default <code>toString</code> to a custom one.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The default from <code>Object</code> returns a technical identifier; a custom override returns a concise, human-readable representation of the object's state.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>If System.out.print or System.out.println is passed an object, that object's `toString` method is called, and the returned `String` is printed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you pass an object to <code>System.out.println</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object's <code>toString</code> method is called and the returned <code>String</code> is printed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which method is invoked to convert an object to text when printing?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>toString</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What gets printed if you call <code>System.out.print(p)</code> on a <code>Point p</code> that overrides <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whatever string is returned by <code>p.toString()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you print an object and see something like <code>Point@1a2b3c</code>. What does that tell you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class hasn't overridden <code>toString</code>, so you're seeing <code>Object</code>'s default implementation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare printing a primitive vs. printing an object with <code>println</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitives are converted to text using built-in conversions; objects are converted by calling their <code>toString</code> method.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`toString` is also used when a reference type is include in a `String` concatenation expression.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When else besides printing is <code>toString</code> called automatically?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a reference type is included in a <code>String</code> concatenation expression.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>"Point: " + p</code> where <code>p</code> is an object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java calls <code>p.toString()</code> and concatenates the result with the string.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>"value=" + someObject</code> not cause a type error?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because Java automatically calls the object's <code>toString</code> to get a <code>String</code> for concatenation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you override <code>toString</code> on <code>Point</code> to return "(x,y)". What does <code>"p=" + new Point(1,2)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>"p=(1,2)"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how <code>toString</code> is used in <code>println</code> vs. in string concatenation.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In both cases Java calls the object's <code>toString</code> automatically to convert the object to a printable <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>`this`</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Within a non-`static` method or a constructor, the keyword `this` is a name for the reference to the current object—the object on which the method was called or the object being constructed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In a non-<code>static</code> method, what does the keyword <code>this</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the current object—the object on which the method was called.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a constructor, what does <code>this</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object currently being constructed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>this</code> not available in a <code>static</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static methods are not called on an instance, so there is no current object for <code>this</code> to refer to.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Given <code>void setX(int x) { this.x = x; }</code>, what does <code>this.x</code> distinguish from just <code>x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>this.x</code> refers to the instance field of the current object, while <code>x</code> alone refers to the parameter.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>this</code> in a constructor differ from <code>this</code> in a regular non-static method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In a constructor it refers to the object being constructed; in a non-static method it refers to the object the method was called on. In both cases it names the current object.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The keyword `this` can be used to pass a reference to the current object as an argument to a method or constructor or as a value to be assigned anywhere a value of the type of the current class is needed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can you pass <code>this</code> as an argument to another method? What does that accomplish?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. It passes a reference to the current object so the called method can operate on it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where can <code>this</code> be used as a value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Anywhere a value of the type of the current class is needed—as an argument, as an assignment source, or as a return value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when an object calls <code>list.add(this)</code> from inside one of its own methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object adds a reference to itself to the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Node</code> method needs to register itself with a <code>Graph</code>. How might <code>this</code> help?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The method can call <code>graph.register(this)</code> to pass its own reference to the graph.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare using <code>this</code> as an argument versus using a separately stored reference to the same object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They refer to the same object, but <code>this</code> is always guaranteed to name the current object without needing an extra variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Comments</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Comments are ignored by the compiler and are not executed when the program is run.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the Java compiler do with comments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It ignores them—they are not part of the compiled program.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are comments executed at runtime?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Since the compiler strips them, there is nothing to execute at runtime.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you write invalid Java syntax inside a comment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing—the compiler ignores the contents of comments, so syntax inside them does not matter.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you "comment out" a line that called a method. Will that method still run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Commented-out code is ignored by the compiler and never executed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare comments to <code>System.out.println</code> calls as a way to document behavior.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Comments are ignored by the compiler and have no runtime effect; <code>println</code> calls actually execute and produce output when the program runs.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Three types of comments in Java include `/* */`, which generates a block of comments, `//`, which generates a comment on one line, and `/** */`, which are Javadoc comments and are used to create API documentation.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the three types of comments in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Block comments <code>/* */</code>, line comments <code>//</code>, and Javadoc comments <code>/** */</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the purpose of a Javadoc comment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To create API documentation from specially formatted comments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which comment style would you use for a single-line note?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>//</code>, the line comment.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to temporarily disable a 10-line block of code. Which comment style is most convenient?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A block comment <code>/* */</code> around the entire region.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>/* */</code> and <code>/** */</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are block comments, but <code>/** */</code> is a Javadoc comment intended to be processed into API documentation, while <code>/* */</code> is a plain comment.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Invariants</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Invariants are things that must be true if the program is working correctly. They help us think about how different parts of a program work together.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an invariant?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Something that must be true if the program is working correctly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are invariants useful when reasoning about a program?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They help us think about how different parts of a program work together by stating what must always hold.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if an invariant is violated at runtime?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The program is not working correctly—there is a bug somewhere.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a bank account class claims its balance is never negative. What is that statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An invariant of the class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an invariant to a regular boolean expression in the code.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A boolean expression just evaluates at one point; an invariant is a claim that some condition must always hold whenever the program is in a correct state.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A precondition is a kind of invariant that defines a condition that must be true before a method is called.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a precondition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A condition that must be true before a method is called.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a precondition a kind of invariant?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—it is an invariant that applies at the moment just before the method is called.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a method is called and its precondition is not true?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller has a bug; the method is not obligated to behave correctly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>sqrt(x)</code> requires <code>x &gt;= 0</code>. What is that requirement called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A precondition of <code>sqrt</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a precondition to a regular <code>if</code> check inside a method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A precondition is a contractual requirement on the caller; an <code>if</code> check inside the method is runtime logic the method itself performs.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A postcondition is kind of invariant that defines a condition that must always be true after a method returns successfully. Postconditions describe the outcome of the execution in terms of the value returned and/or any changes to the state of the world.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a postcondition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A condition that must be true after a method returns successfully.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do postconditions describe?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outcome of the method's execution—the value returned and/or any changes to the state of the world.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a postcondition a kind of invariant?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—it is an invariant that must hold at the moment just after a successful return.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>sort(list)</code> guarantees that the list is in ascending order when it returns. What is that guarantee called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A postcondition of <code>sort</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare preconditions and postconditions.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Preconditions must be true before the method is called (caller's responsibility); postconditions must be true after the method returns successfully (method's responsibility).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The job of a method is to satisfy its postconditions assuming its preconditions have been met. If the preconditions are not met, it is a bug in the code that called the method. If the preconditions were met and the postconditions are not satisfied it is a bug in the method. Methods may or may not actually check that their preconditions have been met.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a method's job, stated in terms of conditions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To satisfy its postconditions, assuming its preconditions have been met.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method is called without its preconditions being met, whose bug is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller's bug.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If preconditions were met but postconditions are not satisfied, whose bug is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The method's bug.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a method required to check its preconditions at runtime?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. A method may or may not actually check that its preconditions have been met.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>divide(a, b)</code> has precondition <code>b != 0</code>. A caller passes <code>0</code> and the program crashes. Whose fault is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller's, because the precondition was violated.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Overloading</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors are said to be overloaded when there are multiple constructors in the same class with different numbers or types of parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When are constructors considered overloaded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a class has multiple constructors with different numbers or types of parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can two constructors in the same class have exactly the same parameter list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No—to be overloaded they must differ in the number or types of parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does overloading constructors allow a class to offer?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Multiple ways to construct an instance, depending on which arguments are available.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Point</code> class has <code>Point()</code> and <code>Point(int x, int y)</code>. Are these overloaded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. They are constructors in the same class with different numbers of parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overloaded constructors to having a single constructor with default values.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java has no default parameter values, so overloading is the standard way to provide multiple construction options.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods are said to be overloaded when there are multiple methods in the same class (or inheritance hierarchy) with the same name but different numbers or types of parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When are methods considered overloaded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When there are multiple methods with the same name but different numbers or types of parameters in the same class or inheritance hierarchy.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can two overloaded methods differ only in return type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No—they must differ in the number or types of their parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does overloading work across a class and its superclass?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—overloading applies within a class or its inheritance hierarchy.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class has <code>print(int x)</code> and <code>print(String s)</code>. Is this overloading?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Same name, different parameter types.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overloaded methods to methods with different names.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Overloaded methods share a name and are distinguished by parameter lists; differently named methods are distinguished by name alone.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When an overloaded constructor or method is called, which one is invoked is determined by finding the constructor or method whose parameter types match the types of the arguments in the call.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How does Java decide which overloaded method to invoke at a call site?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It finds the method whose parameter types match the types of the arguments in the call.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What information is used to resolve overloading?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The argument types at the call site, matched against the parameter types of the candidate methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>At what time is overload resolution performed—compile time or run time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At compile time, based on the static types of the arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class has <code>f(int)</code> and <code>f(double)</code>. You call <code>f(3)</code>. Which is invoked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>f(int)</code>, because the literal <code>3</code> has type <code>int</code>, which matches the <code>int</code> parameter.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overload resolution to method dispatch by name alone.</p></question>
        <answer><p>With unique names, the name alone selects the method; with overloading, the name plus parameter types together select the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Overloading of methods doesn't allow you to do anything you couldn't do by just giving the different methods different names.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Does method overloading give Java any new capabilities?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Anything you can do with overloading you could also do by giving the methods different names.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If method overloading gives no new capabilities beyond what distinct method names could provide, why is it used at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For readability and convenience—related operations can share a single intuitive name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is overloading a runtime feature that changes program behavior beyond naming?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No—it is purely a naming convenience resolved by the compiler.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: instead of overloading <code>print</code>, you write <code>printInt</code> and <code>printString</code>. Have you lost any capability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. You have exactly the same capability, just with longer, more specific names.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overloading to using distinct method names for each signature.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Overloading shares a name for related operations; distinct names make the differences explicit. Both can express the same programs.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Inheritance</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `Object` class in the `java.lang` package is the direct or indirect superclass of all other classes in Java. Other than that, you don't need to know about inheritance for the AP exam.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the ultimate superclass of every class in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Object</code>, in the <code>java.lang</code> package.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>Object</code> is a "direct or indirect" superclass?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A class's superclass chain always eventually reaches <code>Object</code>, whether directly or through other classes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In which package does <code>Object</code> live?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.lang</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write <code>class Dog {}</code> with no <code>extends</code> clause. What is its superclass?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Object</code>, implicitly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a class that directly extends <code>Object</code> to one that extends another class.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both ultimately have <code>Object</code> as an ancestor; one reaches it directly, the other through one or more intermediate superclasses.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All classes inherit from `Object` the methods `boolean equals(Object other)` and `String toString()` which are described in the [AP Java Quick Reference].</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which two methods does every class inherit from <code>Object</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code> and <code>String toString()</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>equals</code>, and what parameter does it take?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns <code>boolean</code> and takes a single <code>Object</code> parameter.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write a new class and never declare <code>equals</code> or <code>toString</code>. Are those methods available on its instances?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—they are inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>equals</code> and <code>toString</code> in terms of purpose.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>equals</code> tests whether two objects are considered equal; <code>toString</code> produces a <code>String</code> representation of an object.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Classes often override the `equals` and `toString` methods with class-specific implementations.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to override <code>equals</code> or <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To provide a class-specific implementation that replaces the one inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do classes often override <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To provide a more informative, class-specific <code>String</code> representation than the default from <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do classes often override <code>equals</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To define equality based on the class's own notion of value, not just reference identity.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Point</code> class overrides <code>equals</code> so that two points with the same coordinates compare equal. Is that allowed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—that is a typical class-specific override of the inherited <code>equals</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an overridden <code>toString</code> with the default one from <code>Object</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The default shows generic information like the class name and a hash; an overridden version typically shows meaningful, class-specific field values.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Built in classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Classes in Java are grouped into packages. The classes `String`, `Math`, `System`, `Integer`, `Double`, `Boolean`, and `Object` are all from the `java.lang` package which is always available in all Java programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are classes organized in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are grouped into packages.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which package contains <code>String</code>, <code>Math</code>, <code>System</code>, <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, <code>Boolean</code>, and <code>Object</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.lang</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is special about the <code>java.lang</code> package?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is always available in all Java programs without needing an import.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you use <code>Math.sqrt</code> without importing anything. Why does this work?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math</code> lives in <code>java.lang</code>, which is implicitly available in every Java program.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>java.lang</code> to other packages in terms of availability.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.lang</code> is automatically available everywhere; classes in other packages must be imported (or referred to by fully qualified name) before use.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The only class we use from another package is `ArrayList` which needs to be imported from `java.util`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which class used in AP CSA comes from a package other than <code>java.lang</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>From which package is <code>ArrayList</code> imported?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.util</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>ArrayList</code> require an import while <code>String</code> does not?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList</code> lives in <code>java.util</code>, which is not automatically available; <code>String</code> lives in <code>java.lang</code>, which is.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you use <code>ArrayList</code> without an import and get a compile error. What should you add?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code> statement at the top of the file.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare importing <code>ArrayList</code> from <code>java.util</code> to using classes from <code>java.lang</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Classes from <code>java.lang</code> need no import; classes from <code>java.util</code> (and other packages) must be imported or fully qualified.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Application program interfaces (APIs) and libraries provide classes we can use in our programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does API stand for?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Application Program Interface.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do APIs and libraries provide to our programs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Classes (and methods) we can use without writing them ourselves.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is using library classes valuable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It saves us from reimplementing common functionality and lets us build on well-tested code.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you need a resizable list and use <code>ArrayList</code> from the standard library. What are you making use of?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A library class provided by Java's API.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare writing a class yourself to using one from an API or library.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Writing it yourself gives full control but takes effort and risks bugs; using a library class gives you tested, ready-made functionality at the cost of learning its interface.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</content>
</invoke>
  <section>
    <title>Strings</title>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String</code> objects are typically created with <code>String</code> literals but can be constructed via constructors defined in the <code>String</code> class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the most common way to create a <code>String</code> object in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using a <code>String</code> literal, such as <code>"hello"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Besides literals, how else can a <code>String</code> object be created?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By calling a constructor defined in the <code>String</code> class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>"hello"</code> a <code>String</code> object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. A <code>String</code> literal creates a <code>String</code> object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare creating a <code>String</code> via a literal versus via <code>new String(...)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both produce <code>String</code> objects, but literals are the typical and preferred way; using the constructor is rarely needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>String s = "cat";</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> literal creates a <code>String</code> object and <code>s</code> is set to reference it.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String</code> objects are immutable; many methods on <code>String</code>s produce new <code>String</code>s that are related to the original (such as the original converted to all upper case) but the original <code>String</code> cannot be changed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>String</code> objects are immutable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once created, a <code>String</code> object's contents cannot be changed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you call <code>s.toUpperCase()</code>, what happens to <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing — <code>s</code> is unchanged. A new <code>String</code> with the uppercase version is returned.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you call a method like <code>toUpperCase()</code> on a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> is produced that is related to the original; the original is not modified.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why must <code>String</code> methods return new <code>String</code>s instead of modifying the original?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>String</code> objects are immutable and cannot be changed after they are created.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast mutability of <code>String</code> with a typical mutable object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A mutable object's state can be changed by calling methods on it; a <code>String</code>'s state cannot — methods only produce new <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String</code> objects can be concatenated using the <code>+</code> or <code>+=</code> operator, resulting in a new <code>String</code> object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What operators can be used to concatenate <code>String</code>s in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>+</code> and <code>+=</code> operators.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the result of <code>"foo" + "bar"</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> object containing <code>"foobar"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>s += "x"</code> change the original <code>String</code> that <code>s</code> referenced?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It creates a new <code>String</code> and reassigns <code>s</code> to reference it. <code>String</code>s are immutable.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of value does <code>+</code> produce when both operands are <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> object formed by concatenation.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>+</code> and <code>+=</code> on <code>String</code>s.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both concatenate and produce a new <code>String</code>; <code>+=</code> additionally reassigns the result back to the left-hand variable.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Non-<code>String</code> values can also be concatenated with a <code>String</code> object. This causes an implicit conversion of the values to <code>String</code> objects. Primitive values and <code>null</code> are converted to their standard literal form and reference types are converted using their <code>toString</code> method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you concatenate an <code>int</code> with a <code>String</code> using <code>+</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>int</code> is implicitly converted to its standard literal form as a <code>String</code> and then concatenated.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a reference type converted to a <code>String</code> during concatenation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By calling its <code>toString</code> method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"x=" + null</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>String</code> <code>"x=null"</code> — <code>null</code> is converted to its literal form <code>"null"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>"value: " + 42</code> compile even though <code>42</code> isn't a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because concatenation with a <code>String</code> implicitly converts non-<code>String</code> values to <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how primitives and reference types are converted in <code>String</code> concatenation.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitives (and <code>null</code>) are converted to their standard literal form; reference types are converted by calling their <code>toString</code> method.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Escape sequences in Strings start with a <code>\</code> and have a special meaning in Java. Escape sequences used in this course include <code>\"</code>, <code>\\</code>, and <code>\n</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What character begins an escape sequence in a Java <code>String</code> literal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The backslash character <code>\</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the escape sequence <code>\n</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A newline character.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you include a double quote inside a <code>String</code> literal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use the escape sequence <code>\"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you include a single backslash in a <code>String</code> literal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>\\</code>, because <code>\</code> alone begins an escape sequence.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you just write <code>"</code> inside a <code>String</code> literal to include a quote?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because an unescaped <code>"</code> would end the literal; you must write <code>\"</code> instead.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A <code>String</code> object has index values from 0 to length – 1. Attempting to access indexes outside this range (i.e. less than 0 or greater than or equal to the length of the String) will result in an <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the range of valid indexes for a <code>String</code> of length <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>n - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you access an invalid index in a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is index <code>length()</code> a valid index into a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Valid indexes only go up to <code>length() - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>s.substring(-1)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> because the index is outside the valid range.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a negative index invalid on a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>String</code> indexes start at 0; anything less than 0 is outside the valid range and causes a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You can think of the index as the number that tells you how far from the front of the string a given character is. Thus the second character in a <code>String</code> has index 1 because there is one character ahead of it. And the first character has index 0 because there are zero characters ahead of it. The length of the string is not a valid index because there is no character in an n-character string that has n characters in front of it.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Conceptually, what does a <code>String</code> index represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>How far from the front of the <code>String</code> a given character is — i.e., how many characters are ahead of it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the first character of a <code>String</code> have index 0?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because there are zero characters ahead of it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What index does the second character of a <code>String</code> have, and why?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Index 1, because there is one character ahead of it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>length()</code> never a valid character index?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because no character in an n-character <code>String</code> has n characters in front of it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>"cat"</code>, what index does <code>'t'</code> have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Index 2, because there are two characters (<code>'c'</code> and <code>'a'</code>) ahead of it.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String(String str)</code> — Constructs a new String object that represents the same sequence of characters as str. There is almost no reason to ever use this constructor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the constructor <code>String(String str)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It constructs a new <code>String</code> object representing the same sequence of characters as <code>str</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is there almost no reason to use <code>new String(str)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>str</code> is already a <code>String</code>, and <code>String</code>s are immutable, so making a copy serves no practical purpose.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of object is produced by <code>new String("hi")</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> object with the same characters as <code>"hi"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast <code>String s = "hi";</code> with <code>String s = new String("hi");</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both give <code>s</code> a <code>String</code> with the characters <code>h</code> and <code>i</code>; the literal form is preferred because the constructor adds no real value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the <code>String(String str)</code> constructor on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, it is listed on the AP Java Quick Reference.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int length()</code> — Returns the number of characters in a String object</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>String</code> method <code>length()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of characters in the <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>String.length()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hello".length()</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>s.length()</code> returns <code>n</code>, what is the largest valid index into <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"".length()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code>, because the empty <code>String</code> contains zero characters.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String substring(int from, int to)</code> — Returns the substring beginning at index <code>from</code> and ending at index <code>to − 1</code></ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>substring(int from, int to)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The substring beginning at index <code>from</code> and ending at index <code>to - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the <code>to</code> index in <code>substring(from, to)</code> inclusive or exclusive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Exclusive — the character at index <code>to</code> is not included.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"abcdef".substring(1, 4)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>"bcd"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many characters are in the result of <code>s.substring(from, to)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>to - from</code> characters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>s.substring(from, to)</code> with <code>to</code> greater than <code>s.length()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String substring(int from)</code> — Equivalent to <code>substring(from, length())</code></ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the single-argument <code>substring(int from)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The substring from index <code>from</code> to the end of the <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What call is <code>s.substring(from)</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>s.substring(from, s.length())</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hello".substring(2)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>"llo"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>s.substring(0)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> equal to <code>s</code> — the entire original <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>substring(int from)</code> with <code>substring(int from, int to)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The one-argument form always runs from <code>from</code> to the end; the two-argument form lets you specify both a start and an exclusive end index.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int indexOf(String str)</code> — Returns the index of the first occurrence of str; returns <code>-1</code> if not found</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>indexOf(String str)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The index of the first occurrence of <code>str</code> in the <code>String</code>, or <code>-1</code> if it is not found.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you tell, using <code>indexOf</code>, whether a <code>String</code> contains another <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Check whether <code>indexOf</code> returns a value other than <code>-1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"banana".indexOf("na")</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>2</code>, the index of the first occurrence of <code>"na"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>indexOf</code> return if the target string is not found?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>-1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a <code>String</code> contains several occurrences of <code>str</code>, which index does <code>indexOf(str)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The index of the first (leftmost) occurrence.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code> — Returns <code>true</code> if other is a String and its text is the same as the text of the <code>String</code> <code>equals</code> was called on. Otherwise returns <code>false</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>String.equals(Object other)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> if <code>other</code> is a <code>String</code> with the same text as the receiver; <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why should you use <code>equals</code> instead of <code>==</code> to compare <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code> compares references; <code>equals</code> compares the actual text of the <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hi".equals("hi")</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hi".equals(new Object())</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code>, because the argument is not a <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>equals</code> consider capitalization when comparing <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. <code>"Hi".equals("hi")</code> returns <code>false</code> because the text must be the same.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int compareTo(String other)</code> — Returns a value &lt; 0 if the <code>String</code> is alphabetically less than <code>other</code>; returns zero if it is <code>equals</code> to <code>other</code>; and returns a value &gt; 0 if it is greater than <code>other</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>compareTo</code> return when two <code>String</code>s are equal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Zero.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a negative return value from <code>s.compareTo(other)</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>s</code> is alphabetically less than <code>other</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a positive return value from <code>s.compareTo(other)</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>s</code> is alphabetically greater than <code>other</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast <code>equals</code> and <code>compareTo</code> for <code>String</code>s.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>equals</code> returns a <code>boolean</code> indicating whether two <code>String</code>s have the same text; <code>compareTo</code> returns an <code>int</code> indicating their alphabetical ordering.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How would you test whether <code>s</code> comes before <code>t</code> alphabetically using <code>compareTo</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Check whether <code>s.compareTo(t) &lt; 0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String[] split(String del)</code> — Returns a <code>String</code> array where each element is a substring of this <code>String</code>, which has been split around matches of the given expression <code>del</code></ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>split(String del)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> array whose elements are the pieces of the original <code>String</code> split around matches of <code>del</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>String.split</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String[]</code> — an array of <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a likely result of <code>"a,b,c".split(",")</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array of three <code>String</code>s: <code>"a"</code>, <code>"b"</code>, and <code>"c"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the argument <code>del</code> play in <code>split</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is the delimiter expression; the <code>String</code> is split around matches of <code>del</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you want to break a sentence into words separated by spaces, what method could you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>split</code>, passing a space (or whitespace pattern) as the delimiter.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A one-character <code>String</code> at index <code>i</code> in the <code>String</code> <code>s</code> can be obtained by calling <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you get a one-character <code>String</code> at index <code>i</code> of <code>String</code> <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Call <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code> yield exactly one character?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>substring</code>'s second argument is exclusive, so the result has length <code>(i + 1) - i = 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"cat".substring(1, 2)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The one-character <code>String</code> <code>"a"</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type is produced by <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code> — a <code>char</code> or a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> (of length 1), not a <code>char</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code> with <code>i</code> equal to <code>s.length()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> because <code>i</code> is outside the valid index range.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>The <code>System</code> class</title>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> display information on the computer monitor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They display information on the computer monitor.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where is output from <code>System.out.print</code> sent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To the computer monitor (standard output).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In AP CSA, which class are <code>print</code> and <code>println</code> typically accessed through?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>System</code> class, via <code>System.out</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you wanted to display a message to the user in a simple Java program, which methods would you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>System.out.print</code> or <code>System.out.println</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of information can <code>System.out.print</code> display?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any information that can be converted to a <code>String</code>, which is then shown on the monitor.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>System.out.println</code> moves the cursor to a new line after the information has been displayed, while <code>System.out.print</code> does not.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the difference between <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>println</code> moves the cursor to a new line after displaying the information; <code>print</code> does not.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you call <code>System.out.print("Hi")</code> twice in a row, what appears on screen?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>HiHi</code> on a single line, because <code>print</code> does not advance to a new line.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you call <code>System.out.println("Hi")</code> twice in a row, what appears on screen?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Hi</code> on one line and <code>Hi</code> on the next, because <code>println</code> advances the cursor to a new line after each call.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which method would you use to display output without ending the current line?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>System.out.print</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the cursor after <code>System.out.println("done")</code> runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It moves to the start of the next line.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>The <code>Math</code> class</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The <code>Math</code> class is part of Java and is available in all Java programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the <code>Math</code> class come from?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is part of Java itself and is available in all Java programs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you need to import the <code>Math</code> class explicitly to use it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is part of Java and available in all Java programs without special setup.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Math</code> a class you have to write yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is provided as part of Java's standard library.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you are writing a brand-new Java program, can you use <code>Math</code> right away?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because <code>Math</code> is available in all Java programs.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of functionality does the <code>Math</code> class provide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Common mathematical operations and constants, available to every Java program.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The <code>Math</code> class contains only static methods.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of methods does the <code>Math</code> class contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only <code>static</code> methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you need to create a <code>Math</code> object to call its methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Because all of <code>Math</code>'s methods are <code>static</code>, you call them on the class itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the correct way to call <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the class: <code>Math.sqrt(x)</code>. You do not need an instance of <code>Math</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>new Math()</code> not something you see in typical code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>Math</code> contains only <code>static</code> methods, so there is no reason to create an instance.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast calling an instance method on a <code>String</code> with calling a method on the <code>Math</code> class.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance methods on a <code>String</code> are called on a specific <code>String</code> object; <code>Math</code> methods are <code>static</code> and are called on the class itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You should know how to use the methods <code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, <code>Math.sqrt</code>, and <code>Math.random</code>. (You should also know about the variable—not a method—<code>Math.PI</code> whose value is the double value that best approximates the value of π.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which four <code>Math</code> methods should you know how to use for the AP exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, <code>Math.sqrt</code>, and <code>Math.random</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> a method or a variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable, not a method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value does <code>Math.PI</code> hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>double</code> value that best approximates π.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which <code>Math</code> member would you use to get the value of π in a calculation?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.PI</code> — it is a variable, not a method, so you don't write parentheses.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might <code>Math.PI()</code> fail to compile?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>PI</code> is a variable, not a method, so you cannot call it with parentheses.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int abs(int x)</code> — Returns the absolute value of an int value</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.abs(int x)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The absolute value of <code>x</code>, as an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>Math.abs(-7)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>7</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of the <code>int</code> version of <code>Math.abs</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.abs</code> do to a non-negative <code>int</code> value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns the value unchanged.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Conceptually, what is the "absolute value" that <code>Math.abs</code> computes?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The magnitude of the number, ignoring its sign.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double abs(double x)</code> — Returns the absolute value of a double value</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>double</code> version of <code>Math.abs</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The absolute value of the <code>double</code> argument, as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>Math.abs(-3.5)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3.5</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>Math</code> have both an <code>int</code> and a <code>double</code> version of <code>abs</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that it can take the absolute value of either <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> arguments and return the same type it received.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type does <code>Math.abs(2.0)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>Math.abs(int)</code> and <code>Math.abs(double)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both return the absolute value of their argument; one takes and returns an <code>int</code>, the other takes and returns a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double pow(double base, double exponent)</code> — Returns the value of the first parameter raised to the power of the second parameter</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.pow(base, exponent)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value of <code>base</code> raised to the power of <code>exponent</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.pow(2, 3)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>8.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How would you compute x squared using <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.pow(x, 2)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the parameter types of <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Two <code>double</code>s: the base and the exponent.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double sqrt(double x)</code> — Returns the positive square root of a double value</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(x)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The positive square root of <code>x</code>, as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>Math.sqrt(16)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>4.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>Math.sqrt</code> return both positive and negative roots?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It returns only the positive square root.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How could you compute the square root of <code>x</code> using <code>Math.pow</code> instead of <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.pow(x, 0.5)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double random()</code> — Returns a double value greater than or equal to 0.0 and less than 1.0.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What range of values does <code>Math.random()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> greater than or equal to <code>0.0</code> and strictly less than <code>1.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can <code>Math.random()</code> ever return exactly <code>1.0</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Its range is <code>[0.0, 1.0)</code>, so <code>1.0</code> is excluded.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can <code>Math.random()</code> return <code>0.0</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. The lower bound <code>0.0</code> is included in its range.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.random()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>Math.random()</code> take any arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is called with no arguments.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Values returned from <code>Math.random</code> are in the range 0.0 to 1.0 but can be manipulated to produce a random int or double in any desired range by scaling (multiplying) and shifting (adding).</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two operations let you turn <code>Math.random()</code> into a value in any desired range?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scaling (multiplying) and shifting (adding).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "scaling" a value from <code>Math.random()</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Multiplying it by some number to stretch its range from <code>[0.0, 1.0)</code> to a wider (or narrower) range.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "shifting" a value from <code>Math.random()</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Adding a constant to move the range up or down.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How could you produce a random <code>double</code> in the range <code>[0.0, 10.0)</code> using <code>Math.random</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Multiply <code>Math.random()</code> by <code>10.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How could you produce a random <code>double</code> in the range <code>[5.0, 15.0)</code> using <code>Math.random</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scale by 10 and shift by 5: <code>Math.random() * 10.0 + 5.0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>ArrayLists</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `ArrayList` class is part of the `java.util` package and needs to be imported to be used in a class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which package contains the <code>ArrayList</code> class?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.util</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must you do before you can use <code>ArrayList</code> in a class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Import it from <code>java.util</code> (e.g. <code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can you use <code>String</code> without an import but not <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> lives in <code>java.lang</code>, which is imported automatically. <code>ArrayList</code> lives in <code>java.util</code>, which must be imported explicitly.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to use <code>ArrayList</code> in a file without importing it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler reports an error saying the symbol <code>ArrayList</code> cannot be found.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What import statement brings in <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An `ArrayList` object is mutable and contains object references.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to say an <code>ArrayList</code> is "mutable"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its contents can be changed after it is created: you can add, remove, and replace elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does an <code>ArrayList</code> store objects directly or references to them?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It stores object references, not the objects themselves.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two <code>ArrayList</code>s both contain a reference to the same object and that object is mutated, what do both lists see?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both lists see the mutation, because they hold references to the same underlying object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does an <code>ArrayList</code> being mutable contrast with a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> is immutable: its characters can't change. An <code>ArrayList</code>'s contents can be modified in place.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an <code>ArrayList</code> hold primitive <code>int</code> values directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It stores object references, so primitives must be wrapped (e.g. in <code>Integer</code>).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The no-argument `ArrayList` constructor constructs an empty list.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;()</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new, empty <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> containing zero elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the size of a newly constructed <code>ArrayList</code> made with the no-argument constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; nums = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code>, what does <code>nums.size()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you create an empty list of <code>Double</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>get(0)</code> on a freshly constructed empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because there is no element at index 0.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Indexes for an `ArrayList` start at `0` and end at `size() − 1`, inclusive.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the index of the first element of an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the index of the last element of a non-empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size() - 1</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>list.size()</code> is 7, what is the range of valid indexes?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0 through 6, inclusive.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>ArrayList</code> indexing compare to array indexing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are the same: both start at 0 and end at length/size minus 1.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the index <code>size()</code> itself a valid index for <code>get</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. The largest valid index for <code>get</code> is <code>size() - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Trying to access an index outside the valid range (e.g. with the `get`, `set` or `remove` method) will cause an `IndexOutOfBoundsException` to be thrown.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you call <code>get</code> with an invalid index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which <code>ArrayList</code> methods can throw <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>get</code>, <code>set</code>, and <code>remove</code> (and <code>add</code> with an index), when given an out-of-range index.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>list.size()</code> is 3, what happens when you call <code>list.get(3)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because valid indexes are 0, 1, 2.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a negative index valid for an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. A negative index causes an <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> a checked or unchecked exception?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is unchecked (a subclass of <code>RuntimeException</code>), so the compiler does not force you to handle it.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Changing the size of an `ArrayList` while traversing it using an enhanced `for` loop will cause a `ConcurrentModificationException` to be thrown. When using an enhanced `for` loop to traverse an `ArrayList`, you should not add or remove elements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What exception do you get if you add or remove elements while traversing an <code>ArrayList</code> with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ConcurrentModificationException</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is it safe to replace an element with <code>set</code> during an enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because <code>set</code> does not change the size of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of loop should you use if you need to remove elements from an <code>ArrayList</code> during traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An indexed <code>for</code> (or <code>while</code>) loop, so you can safely shift the index after removal.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does modifying size during an enhanced <code>for</code> loop fail rather than silently misbehave?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The iterator detects that the list was modified out from under it and throws <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> to signal the problem.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does merely reading elements with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop cause any exception?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Reading is safe; the problem is only with structural changes (add/remove).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`ArrayList` is a generic type which means we can write the type `ArrayList&lt;E&gt;` to mean an `ArrayList` that can only contain values of the type `E`. E.g. `ArrayList&lt;String&gt;` is a list of `String`s.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>ArrayList</code> is a "generic" type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is parameterized by a type; you write <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> to specify what kind of elements the list contains.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type of elements does an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only <code>String</code> references.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens at compile time if you try to add a non-<code>String</code> to an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler rejects it with a type error.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> differ from <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They differ only in the element type they accept; the list behavior is the same.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compared to a plain <code>ArrayList</code>, what does parameterizing with a type give you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile-time type checking so that only the right element type can go in, and no casts are needed when taking elements out.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E` is called a "type parameter" because it is filled in with a specific type like `String`. Type parameters have to be reference types.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code>, what is <code>E</code> called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A type parameter.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of types are allowed as type parameters in Java generics?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only reference types (classes, interfaces, other generics). Primitive types are not allowed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you write <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>int</code> is a primitive type, and type parameters must be reference types. Use <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> instead.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a type parameter "filled in"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By supplying a specific reference type at the use site, e.g. <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> fills <code>E</code> with <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the type parameter a "parameter"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because, like a method parameter takes a value, a type parameter takes a type — supplied by the code that uses the generic class.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When `ArrayList&lt;E&gt;` is specified, the types of the parameters in methods that accept elements, e.g. `add`, and the return types of methods that return elements, e.g. `get`, will be `E`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>For an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, what is the parameter type of <code>add</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> — wherever the declaration says <code>E</code>, it becomes <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, what is the return type of <code>get</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does specifying <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> affect the signatures of its methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All occurrences of <code>E</code> in the method signatures are replaced by the specific type supplied.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why don't you need a cast on the result of <code>get</code> when using a parameterized <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the return type is already the specific element type <code>E</code>, not <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In an <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code>, what type does <code>set(int, E)</code> take as its second argument?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Double</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The type `ArrayList&lt;E&gt;` is preferred over the so-called "raw" type `ArrayList` because it allows the compiler to find errors that would otherwise be found at run-time.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "raw" <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> written without a type parameter, like plain <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> preferred over the raw type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it lets the compiler catch type errors at compile time instead of failing at run time.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of errors does using the raw type tend to push into run time?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ClassCastException</code>s and other type mismatches that could have been caught statically.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you assign a mixed bag of objects into a raw <code>ArrayList</code>, when do problems usually surface?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At run time, when code pulls an element out and casts it to the wrong type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the general lesson about compile-time vs run-time errors from generics?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Catching errors at compile time is better: the problem is found before the program runs.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Typically you invoke the `ArrayList` constructor as `ArrayList&lt;&gt;()`, i.e. with nothing between the `&lt;&gt;`s as the Java compiler will infer the correct element type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "diamond" in <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The empty <code>&lt;&gt;</code>, which tells the compiler to infer the element type from context.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; xs = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code>, what type does the compiler infer on the right?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>, taken from the declared type of <code>xs</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the diamond preferred over repeating the type parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It avoids repetition and the compiler can figure out the type automatically.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>new ArrayList()</code> (no diamond) the same as <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Without any <code>&lt;&gt;</code> you are using the raw type, which defeats generic type checking.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the compiler get the type information when you write <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From the target type on the left side of the assignment (or from method parameter types, etc.).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Iteration statements can be used to access all the elements in an `ArrayList`. This is called traversing the `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is meant by "traversing" an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Visiting each element in turn using an iteration statement.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which kinds of loops can be used to traverse an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Indexed <code>for</code> loops, <code>while</code> loops, and enhanced <code>for</code> loops.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Write a simple traversal of <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; xs</code> using an enhanced <code>for</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for (String s : xs) { System.out.println(s); }</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is traversing an <code>ArrayList</code> similar to traversing an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You visit elements in order by index, typically from 0 to the last valid index.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is traversal important for list algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Most list algorithms need to examine or process every element, which requires some form of traversal.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>There are standard `ArrayList` algorithms that utilize traversals to insert and delete elements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do standard <code>ArrayList</code> insertion/deletion algorithms rely on?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing the list to find the right position(s) and then inserting or deleting elements there.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an insertion task on an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Inserting a new value into a sorted list so the list stays in order.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a deletion task on an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Removing all elements that meet some condition, such as all negative numbers.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are insertion and deletion often bundled with traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You must traverse the list to locate the elements that need to be inserted next to or removed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does an insertion into the middle of an <code>ArrayList</code> do to following elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It shifts them one position to the right to make room.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Deleting elements during a traversal of an `ArrayList` requires using special techniques to avoid skipping elements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why does naive deletion during traversal skip elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Removing an element shifts later elements left by one, so advancing the index normally jumps over the element that moved into the current position.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>One standard technique for deleting from an <code>ArrayList</code> during traversal is...?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Don't increment the index on iterations where you remove an element, so the next iteration examines the shifted-in element.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is another technique for safely deleting from an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traverse from the end toward the beginning, so removals don't affect indexes you haven't visited yet.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you just use an enhanced <code>for</code> loop to delete elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> when the list's size changes during iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What bug appears if you delete an element with <code>remove(i)</code> and then write <code>i++</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You skip over the element that was shifted into index <code>i</code>, failing to examine it.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Most algorithms that work with arrays work equally well with `ArrayList`s after switching `.length` to `.size()` and array accesses and assignments to `get` and `set` calls.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you translate <code>a.length</code> from an array to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>a.size()</code> instead.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you translate <code>a[i]</code> (read) from an array to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>a.get(i)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you translate <code>a[i] = x</code> from an array to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>a.set(i, x)</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you usually have to rewrite the logic of an array algorithm when porting it to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — the structure stays the same; only the syntax for length and element access changes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the straightforward syntactic translation between array and <code>ArrayList</code> algorithms work without rewriting the logic?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s both provide O(1) indexed access to elements; only the syntax differs.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Some algorithms require multiple `String`, array, or `ArrayList` objects to be traversed simultaneously.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "parallel traversal"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing two or more collections at the same time, typically stepping through them in lockstep by index.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an algorithm needing parallel traversal.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Comparing two arrays element by element to decide whether they are equal.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When parallel-traversing two <code>ArrayList</code>s, what should you typically check first?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That they have compatible sizes for the operation you're performing.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't an enhanced <code>for</code> loop always handle parallel traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It exposes only one element at a time from one collection; you usually need an index to access both collections at the same position.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name another scenario that requires simultaneous traversal of two sequences.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Merging two sorted lists into one sorted list.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`int size()` — Returns the number of elements in the list</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>ArrayList.size()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of elements currently in the list, as an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>size()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>size()</code> on an <code>ArrayList</code> different from <code>length</code> on an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size()</code> is a method call with parentheses; <code>length</code> is a field access without parentheses.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>size()</code> return for a freshly constructed empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In an indexed loop, how would you use <code>size()</code> to traverse an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; list.size(); i++) { ... }</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`boolean add(E obj)` — Appends `obj` to end of list; returns `true`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does <code>add(E obj)</code> place the new element?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the end of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>add(E obj)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After calling <code>list.add(x)</code>, by how much does <code>size()</code> increase?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By one.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the index of the element just appended with <code>add(obj)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size() - 1</code> after the call.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the one-argument <code>add</code> differ from the two-argument <code>add</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The one-argument form always appends at the end; the two-argument form inserts at a specific index.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`void add(int index, E obj)` — Inserts `obj` at position `index` which must be a valid index or the current size of the list, increasing the size of the list by one.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>add(int index, E obj)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Inserts <code>obj</code> at position <code>index</code>, shifting existing elements from that position onward one step to the right.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What range of indexes is valid for <code>add(int, E)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>size()</code> inclusive.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>size()</code> itself a valid index for <code>add(int, E)</code> but not for <code>get</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because inserting at <code>size()</code> means appending at the end, which is a valid position; there's no element at <code>size()</code> yet to read with <code>get</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>By how much does the list's size change after a call to <code>add(int, E)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It increases by one.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the element formerly at index <code>i</code> when you call <code>add(i, x)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It moves to index <code>i + 1</code> (along with all following elements).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E get(int index)` — Returns the element at position `index` in the list</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>get(int index)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element at the given position in the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, what type does <code>get</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> — the list's element type <code>E</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown if the index passed to <code>get</code> is out of range?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>get</code> remove the element from the list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It just returns a reference to it, leaving the list unchanged.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the <code>ArrayList</code> equivalent of the array expression <code>a[i]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>a.get(i)</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E set(int index, E obj)` — Replaces the element at position `index` with `obj`; returns the element formerly at position index.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>set(int index, E obj)</code> do to the list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Replaces the element at <code>index</code> with <code>obj</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>set</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element that was previously at that position.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>set</code> change the size of the list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It only overwrites an existing element.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the <code>ArrayList</code> equivalent of the array assignment <code>a[i] = x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>a.set(i, x)</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is it safe to use <code>set</code> on an <code>ArrayList</code> while traversing it with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because <code>set</code> does not change the size of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E remove(int index)` — Removes the element from position `index`, moving elements at position `index + 1` and higher to the left, and decreases the size of the list by one. Returns the element formerly at position `index`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>remove(int index)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element that was at position <code>index</code> before removal.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to elements after the removed index?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They all shift one position to the left.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>remove(int)</code> affect the list's size?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It decreases the size by one.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After <code>list.remove(i)</code>, what's at index <code>i</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element that was previously at index <code>i + 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can <code>remove(int)</code> cause index-skipping bugs during an indexed traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If you still increment the index after a removal, you skip over the element that was shifted into the current position.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Wrapper classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The College Board is weirdly obsessed with wrapper classes.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which topic does the College Board place unusual emphasis on for AP CSA?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Wrapper classes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are "wrapper classes" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Reference classes like <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, and <code>Boolean</code> that wrap primitive values as objects.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the AP curriculum care so much about wrapper classes even though real code rarely uses them directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They're the only way to put primitive values into generic collections like <code>ArrayList</code>, so they show up on the exam.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name the three wrapper classes you need to know for AP CSA.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, and <code>Boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is wrapper-class mastery practically critical in day-to-day Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Not really — autoboxing handles most of it — but it's a recurring AP exam topic.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `Integer`, `Double`, and `Boolean` classes exist primarily because generic types like `ArrayList` can only use reference types as their type parameters. The wrapper classes exist to "wrap" a primitive value in an object so it can be put into an `ArrayList` or used with another generic class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why do wrapper classes like <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code> exist?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that primitive values can be represented as objects and used with generic classes that require reference types.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't generics use primitive types directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java's generic type parameters are restricted to reference types.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "wrap" a primitive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To put its value inside an object of the corresponding wrapper class so it can be treated as a reference.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which wrapper would you use to store a list of <code>boolean</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Boolean</code>, in an <code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you write <code>ArrayList&lt;double&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code> is a primitive type. You need the reference wrapper <code>Double</code>: <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In general you do not need to explicitly use wrapper classes because the Java compiler will automatically wrap a primitive type used in a context where its wrapper type is expected. This is called "autoboxing". Conversely, if a wrapper type is used in a context where the corresponding primitive type is expected it will be automatically "unboxed" and converted to the primitive value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "autoboxing"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The automatic conversion by the compiler of a primitive value into its wrapper object when a wrapper type is expected.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is "unboxing"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The automatic conversion of a wrapper object back into its primitive value when a primitive type is expected.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; xs = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(); xs.add(5);</code>, which mechanism is at work?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Autoboxing: the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code> is wrapped into an <code>Integer</code> automatically.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>int n = xs.get(0);</code> where <code>xs</code> is an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, what happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Unboxing: the returned <code>Integer</code> is automatically converted to its underlying <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do autoboxing and unboxing happen at compile time or run time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler inserts the conversion calls, but the actual boxing/unboxing executes at run time.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You will almost never write code where you declare the type of a variable or parameter or the return type of a method to be one of the wrapper types; just use primitive types and let autoboxing take care of things.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In idiomatic Java, what types should you prefer for variables, parameters, and return values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitive types like <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Should you usually declare a method that returns a count as returning <code>int</code> or <code>Integer</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> — use the primitive and let autoboxing handle conversion if needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why prefer primitives to wrapper types for locals and parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are simpler, faster, and avoid <code>null</code>; autoboxing handles the few places a wrapper is actually needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If primitives are preferred, why do wrapper types ever appear at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In places that require reference types, most commonly the type parameters of generic collections.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What problem does using <code>Integer</code> as a parameter type introduce that <code>int</code> avoids?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>Integer</code> parameter can be <code>null</code>, which can cause <code>NullPointerException</code> on unboxing.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Then one place you will have to use `Integer` and `Double` is when you declare an `ArrayList`: You have to write `ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;` rather than `ArrayList&lt;int&gt;`, `ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;` rather than `ArrayList&lt;double&gt;` and `ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;` rather than `ArrayList&lt;boolean&gt;`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you declare an <code>ArrayList</code> of integers?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, using the wrapper type.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you write <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because type parameters must be reference types, and <code>int</code> is a primitive.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the correct list type for <code>double</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the correct list type for <code>boolean</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Once you've declared an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, can you still add plain <code>int</code> values to it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — autoboxing wraps each <code>int</code> into an <code>Integer</code> automatically.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Integer(int value)` — Constructs a new Integer object that represents the specified int value. This is roughly equivalent to what happens when an int is autoboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the constructor <code>Integer(int value)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Constructs a new <code>Integer</code> object that represents the given <code>int</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the rough equivalent of <code>new Integer(5)</code> in modern Java code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just using the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code> in a context where an <code>Integer</code> is expected, letting autoboxing create the object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is explicit use of <code>new Integer(x)</code> related to autoboxing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Autoboxing does roughly what that constructor call does: wrap the <code>int</code> inside an <code>Integer</code> object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is calling <code>new Integer(x)</code> necessary in day-to-day Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — autoboxing handles it automatically wherever an <code>Integer</code> is needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the parameter type of the <code>Integer</code> constructor on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`int intValue()` — Returns the value of an Integer as an int. This is equivalent to what happens when an Integer is unboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>intValue()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>int</code> value represented by the <code>Integer</code> object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What autoboxing operation is <code>intValue()</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Unboxing — converting an <code>Integer</code> back into its underlying <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>int n = someInteger;</code>, which method is conceptually being called?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>intValue()</code> on the <code>Integer</code>, inserted automatically as part of unboxing.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>intValue()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why don't you usually need to call <code>intValue()</code> explicitly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because unboxing happens automatically whenever you use an <code>Integer</code> where an <code>int</code> is expected.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Integer.MAX_VALUE` — The maximum value that can be represented by an int.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The largest value that can be stored in a Java <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> a method or a field?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A static field (constant) of the <code>Integer</code> class.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> commonly used in "find the minimum" algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As an initial value for the running minimum, so that any real element will be smaller.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you add 1 to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It overflows and wraps around to <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Roughly how large is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About 2.1 billion (2^31 - 1).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Integer.MIN_VALUE` — The minimum value that can be represented by an int.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The smallest (most negative) value that can be stored in a Java <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> commonly used in "find the maximum" algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As an initial value for the running maximum, so that any real element will be larger.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>-Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> equal to <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> is one less than <code>-Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> because of two's-complement asymmetry.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you compute <code>-Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It overflows and gives back <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> again.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> positive or negative?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Negative.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Double(double value)` — Constructs a new Double object that represents the specified double value. This is roughly equivalent to what happens when a double is autoboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>Double(double value)</code> constructor do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Creates a new <code>Double</code> object wrapping the given <code>double</code> value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why would autoboxing replace most uses of <code>new Double(x)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the compiler automatically wraps a <code>double</code> in a <code>Double</code> wherever a <code>Double</code> is expected.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In modern Java, how would you turn a <code>double</code> into a <code>Double</code> idiomatically?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just use the <code>double</code> where a <code>Double</code> is expected and let autoboxing do it.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the parameter type of the <code>Double</code> constructor on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>new Double(3.14)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>Double</code> object representing the value <code>3.14</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`double doubleValue()` — Returns the value of a Double as a double. This is equivalent to what happens when a Double is unboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>doubleValue()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>double</code> value held by a <code>Double</code> object.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which autoboxing operation is <code>doubleValue()</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Unboxing — converting a <code>Double</code> back into its underlying <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>doubleValue()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When would you call <code>doubleValue()</code> explicitly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Almost never in modern code — unboxing happens automatically wherever a <code>double</code> is needed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>double d = someDouble;</code>, what is conceptually happening?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler invokes <code>doubleValue()</code> on the <code>Double</code> to unbox it to a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The College Board does not expect you to know about any methods from the `Boolean` class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the College Board expect you to know about <code>Boolean</code> methods on the AP CSA exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing — no <code>Boolean</code> methods are required.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Despite not needing its methods, why should you still know about the <code>Boolean</code> class at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you need it to store <code>boolean</code> values in generic collections, like <code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Boolean</code> on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only as a wrapper type for use with generics; no specific methods are listed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you still autobox a <code>boolean</code> into a <code>Boolean</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — autoboxing works for <code>Boolean</code> just like for <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If the exam asks about a <code>Boolean</code> method, what's a reasonable assumption?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That the question is out of scope — the AP curriculum does not test <code>Boolean</code> class methods.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Algorithms</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>We can compare algorithms informally by counting statement executions. For instance, sometimes it's useful to analyze a loop to determine either exactly or approximately how many times it will execute its body. More rigorously we can characterize algorithms by how their run time grows as the size of the problem grows.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is one informal way to compare algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By counting how many statements each one executes for a given input.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a more rigorous way to characterize an algorithm's performance?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By describing how its run time grows as the size of the problem grows.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why analyze how many times a loop body runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the number of loop-body executions is often the dominant cost of an algorithm.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to describe an algorithm in terms of growth rate rather than exact counts?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You focus on how work scales with input size, not the exact number of operations for a specific input.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is growth rate more useful than exact statement counts in practice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Growth rate is independent of specific machines and constants and predicts behavior as inputs get large.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Compute statistics about numbers in an array or `ArrayList` such as the sum, average, minimum, and maximum value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name four standard statistics that array/<code>ArrayList</code> algorithms compute.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Sum, average, minimum, and maximum.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is the average of a list computed in terms of other statistics?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Sum of the elements divided by the count of elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's a common initial value for a running maximum when scanning a list of <code>int</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>, or the first element of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's a common initial value for a running minimum when scanning a list of <code>int</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, or the first element of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of loop shape is used for summing a list's elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traversal that keeps a running total, adding each element on every iteration.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine if at least one element of an array or `ArrayList` has a particular property</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does an "exists"-style traversal compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether at least one element in the collection satisfies a given property.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's a typical return value of an "exists"-style traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>boolean</code>: <code>true</code> if a matching element is found, <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What optimization can an "exists" traversal use as soon as it finds a match?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can return <code>true</code> immediately without checking the remaining elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If an "exists"-style traversal's loop finishes without finding a matching element, what should it return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an "exists" query on an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Is there any negative number in the list?"</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine if all elements of an array or `ArrayList` have a particular property</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a "for-all"-style traversal compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether every element in the collection satisfies a given property.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a "for-all"-style traversal, as soon as you find a single counter-example, what can the algorithm do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Return <code>false</code> immediately.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a "for-all"-style traversal's loop finishes without finding a counter-example, what should it return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is the "all" check logically related to the "exists" check?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"All elements have property P" is the same as "no element fails to have property P" — the negation of an "exists not-P" check.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an "all" query on an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Are all strings in this list non-empty?"</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Access all consecutive pairs of elements of an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to access "consecutive pairs" of elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To look at elements at indexes <code>i</code> and <code>i+1</code> together for each valid <code>i</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the last valid value of <code>i</code> in a consecutive-pair loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size() - 2</code> (so that <code>i+1</code> is still a valid index).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example algorithm that uses consecutive pairs.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Checking whether a list is in strictly increasing order by comparing each element to the next.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you easily traverse consecutive pairs with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop alone?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Not easily — you'd need to remember the previous element yourself; an indexed loop is more natural.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For a list of size <code>n</code>, how many consecutive pairs are there?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n - 1</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the presence or absence of duplicate elements in an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What question does a duplicate-detection algorithm answer?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether the collection contains two or more equal elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe a straightforward nested-loop approach to duplicate detection.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For each index <code>i</code>, compare <code>list.get(i)</code> to every <code>list.get(j)</code> with <code>j &gt; i</code>, returning <code>true</code> on a match.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What Java operator should you typically use to compare object elements for equality in these algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>equals</code>, not <code>==</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's one way to detect duplicates more efficiently if the list is sorted?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scan consecutive pairs and check whether any adjacent pair is equal.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What should a duplicate-detection method return if no duplicates are found?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the number of elements in an array or `ArrayList` meeting specific criteria</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a "counting" traversal compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>How many elements of the collection satisfy some criterion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a counting traversal of a collection, what data type is typically used for the running count?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a counting traversal of a collection, what is the initial value of the counter?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a counting traversal's loop, what do you do when an element matches the criterion?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Increment the counter by 1.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example counting query on an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"How many values in the list are even?"</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Shift or rotate elements of an array or `ArrayList` left or right.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does "shifting" elements of a list mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Moving elements to adjacent positions in a consistent direction, typically leaving a gap or dropping an element at one end.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does "rotation" differ from shifting?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Rotation wraps elements around: an element that falls off one end is placed at the other end.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After rotating a list one position to the right, where does the last element end up?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At index 0, as the new first element.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does a left shift by 1 move elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each element at index <code>i &gt; 0</code> moves to index <code>i - 1</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a left shift (not rotation), what typically happens to the leftmost element?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is dropped off the front (or conceptually lost), and some default value may fill the last spot.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Reverse the order of the elements of an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a reversal algorithm do to a list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Puts the elements in the opposite order: the first becomes last, the second becomes second-to-last, and so on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe an in-place reversal using two indexes.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use indexes at the two ends, swap their elements, then move inward until they meet in the middle.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many swaps does an in-place reversal perform on a list of size <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About <code>n / 2</code> swaps.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you reverse a list by copying into a new list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — traverse the original list from the end and append each element to the new list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's one off-by-one pitfall in in-place reversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Stopping the loop too late and swapping elements back to their original positions.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the frequency with which a specific criterion is met by elements within an array or `ArrayList`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is determining "frequency" similar to counting?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both tally how many elements meet a criterion, producing an integer count.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "frequency" of a value in a list, informally?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of elements in the list equal to that value.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe a traversal that counts how often a specific <code>String</code> appears in an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Loop through each element, and each time it <code>equals</code> the target, increment a counter.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In list-algorithm vocabulary, what's the difference between a "count" traversal and a "frequency" traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are essentially the same operation; "frequency" typically emphasizes counting specific matching values.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value should a frequency method return if the target is not present?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Identify the individual digits in an integer</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you extract the last digit of a positive integer <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n % 10</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you "remove" the last digit from a positive integer <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n / 10</code> (integer division).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What loop pattern extracts digits of an integer one at a time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Repeatedly take <code>n % 10</code>, then set <code>n = n / 10</code>, until <code>n</code> becomes 0.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In what order do digits come out of a <code>% 10</code>/<code>/ 10</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From least significant to most significant.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What special case should a digit-extraction loop consider?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value <code>0</code>, which has one digit but whose loop body never runs if you only loop while <code>n &gt; 0</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Find if one or more substrings has a particular property</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of string algorithm checks whether "one or more substrings" has a property?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traversal that looks at substrings of the string and tests each for the property.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What method is commonly used to extract substrings in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>substring</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a property such an algorithm might check.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether any substring is a palindrome, or whether a particular target substring appears.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type typical of an "exists substring with property" check?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What loop bounds would you use to visit every substring of length <code>k</code> in a string of length <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Start indexes from 0 to <code>n - k</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the number of substrings that meet specific criteria</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is counting substrings similar to counting list elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both involve traversing all candidates and incrementing a counter whenever one meets the criterion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a substring-counting algorithm return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of substrings that satisfy the given condition.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a substring-counting problem.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Counting the number of occurrences of the letter <code>"a"</code> in a string.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might a substring-counting loop be nested?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you may need to iterate over all possible start indexes and possibly end indexes (or lengths).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the total number of substrings of a string of length <code>n</code> (all lengths &gt;= 1)?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n * (n + 1) / 2</code></p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Create a new `String` with the characters reversed</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why do you have to create a new <code>String</code> when "reversing" a string?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>String</code>s are immutable, so you can't modify the original in place.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe a loop-based approach to reversing a string <code>s</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Build up a result by traversing <code>s</code> from the last index back to 0, appending each character to the result.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which <code>String</code> method returns a character at a given index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>charAt(int index)</code></p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value does the reverse of an empty string equal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The empty string <code>""</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is "reverse a string" the same operation as "reverse an <code>ArrayList</code>"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conceptually yes, but strings are immutable so you must produce a new string rather than swapping in place.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Sequential/linear search algorithms check each element in order until the desired value is found or all elements in the array or `ArrayList` have been checked. You should be able to write code that performs a linear search.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How does linear (sequential) search work?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It checks each element in order from the start until it finds the target or reaches the end.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does linear search return when the target is not present?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Typically <code>-1</code> or <code>false</code>, depending on the signature.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does linear search require the list to be sorted?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It works on any list, sorted or unsorted.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the worst-case number of comparisons for linear search on a list of size <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n</code> comparisons.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>On the AP exam, should you be prepared to write a linear search yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — you should be able to write code that performs a linear search.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Binary search algorithms can search sorted lists much more efficiently than linear search, finding elements in log N time where N is the size of the list. You are unlikely to need to write a binary search yourself for the exam.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why is binary search faster than linear search?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its run time grows as <code>log N</code> rather than <code>N</code>, so it scales much better to large lists.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What precondition does binary search require?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The list must already be sorted.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the big-O running time of binary search?</p></question>
        <answer><p>O(log N), where N is the size of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are you expected to write a binary search from scratch on the AP exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — it's unlikely you'll have to write one, but you should understand how it works.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Roughly how many steps does binary search need for a list of a million elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About 20 (since <code>log2(1,000,000)</code> is about 20).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The binary search algorithm starts at the middle of a sorted array or `ArrayList` and on average eliminates half of the elements in each iteration until the desired value is found or all elements have been eliminated.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does binary search begin its search?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the middle element of the sorted list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How much of the remaining search space is eliminated each iteration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About half.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After comparing the target to the middle element, how does binary search decide which half to continue searching?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If the target is less than the middle, search the left half; if greater, search the right half.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When does binary search stop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When it finds the target or the search range becomes empty.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is halving the list each step what gives binary search its log N running time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you can halve <code>N</code> only about <code>log2 N</code> times before reaching 1.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The binary search algorithm can be written either iteratively or recursively.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can binary search be implemented with a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — the iterative version uses a loop that updates <code>low</code> and <code>high</code> bounds.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can binary search be implemented recursively?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — the recursive version calls itself on a smaller half of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In the recursive version, what is the base case?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An empty range (the target isn't present) or the middle element equals the target.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do the iterative and recursive versions of binary search have the same running time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — both are O(log N).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is binary search a good example of "iteration vs recursion"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the same algorithm can be expressed naturally in either style with equivalent behavior.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Selection sort and insertion sort are iterative sorting algorithms that can be used to sort elements in an array or ArrayList. You should be able to recognize them but will not have to write them yourself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Are selection sort and insertion sort iterative or recursive algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iterative — they use loops rather than recursion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are you expected to write selection sort or insertion sort from scratch on the AP exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — you only need to be able to recognize them.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the basic idea of selection sort?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Repeatedly find the smallest remaining element and swap it into the next position at the front of the list.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the basic idea of insertion sort?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Grow a sorted prefix by taking each next element and inserting it into its correct spot within the already-sorted portion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can these sorts be applied to an <code>ArrayList</code> as well as an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — the ideas work on either, using <code>get</code>/<code>set</code> instead of array indexing.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Merge sort is a recursive sorting algorithm that can be used to sort elements in an array or ArrayList. You will not have to be able to write a merge sort.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Is merge sort iterative or recursive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Recursive — it divides the list and recursively sorts each half.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Will the AP exam ask you to implement merge sort yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — you only need to understand its behavior conceptually.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What two phases does merge sort have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A recursive "divide and sort" phase, and a "merge" phase that combines two sorted halves into one sorted result.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is merge sort's running time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>O(N log N), which is asymptotically faster than selection or insertion sort on large lists.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can merge sort be used on both arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — conceptually it works on any indexable sequence of elements.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Recursion</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A recursive method is a method that calls itself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a recursive method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method that calls itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In AP CSA, what kind of recursion are you expected to know about?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Simple direct recursion, where a method calls itself by name.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a method that calls another method that happens to call it considered directly recursive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — that is mutual recursion; AP CSA focuses on direct recursion where the method calls itself.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens at the machine level when a recursive method calls itself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new stack frame is pushed with its own copy of local variables and parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a recursive method also use loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — recursion and iteration can appear together in the same method.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Recursive methods contain at least one base case, which halts the recursion, and at least one recursive call.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two things must every recursive method have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At least one base case and at least one recursive call.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the base case do in a recursive method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It handles a simple input directly without recursing further, stopping the recursion.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a recursive method has no base case, or the base case is never reached?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Infinite recursion occurs, eventually causing a <code>StackOverflowError</code>.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a recursive call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A call the method makes to itself, usually on a smaller or simpler input.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it important that the recursive call move toward the base case?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Otherwise the recursion won't terminate and the program will run forever (or crash).</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each recursive call has its own set of local variables, including its parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Do recursive calls share local variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Each call has its own independent set of local variables and parameters.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it important that each recursive call have its own independent set of local variables and parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets each recursive call keep its own state, so updates in one call don't clobber another.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where are a recursive method's per-call local variables stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the call stack, in a new stack frame created for each invocation of the method.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a recursive method has a parameter <code>int n</code>, does each call share the same <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — each call has its own <code>n</code>, whose value depends on what was passed in.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to a call's local variables when that call returns?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its stack frame is popped and those local variables go out of scope.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Parameter values capture the progress of a recursive process, much like loop control variable values capture the progress of a loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What role do parameter values play in recursion?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They capture the progress of the recursive process — where in the computation a given call is working.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role do loop control variables play in a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They capture the progress of the loop — which iteration or index it is currently on.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the analogy between recursive parameters and loop control variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both track "how far along" the computation is; parameters serve that role for recursion that control variables serve for loops.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>factorial(int n)</code>, what does the parameter <code>n</code> tell you about the recursion's progress?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It indicates which sub-problem (<code>n!</code>) the current call is solving; smaller <code>n</code> means closer to the base case.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why shouldn't a recursive method just use global state to track progress?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because parameters per call keep each recursion's state cleanly separated, avoiding interference between calls.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Recursion can be used to traverse linear structures like `String`s, arrays, and `ArrayList`s but it is most useful for traversing tree structures which are difficult to traverse with simple loops.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can recursion traverse a linear structure like an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, by recursing on a smaller subrange of the structure.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of structure does recursion especially shine at traversing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Tree structures, where simple loops don't naturally fit.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name three linear structures you could traverse recursively.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>s, arrays, and <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are trees harder to traverse with simple loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because trees branch at each node, so a single loop can't naturally follow all the branches without extra data structures.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What makes recursion a natural fit for trees?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Trees are themselves defined recursively — a tree is a node with subtrees — so a recursive traversal mirrors the structure.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Any recursive solution can be replicated through the use of an iterative approach. However some recursions, such as tree recursions, will require maintaining extra data structures to keep track of the information that would otherwise be managed by the process of recursion.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can every recursive algorithm be rewritten iteratively?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, in principle any recursive solution has an iterative equivalent.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the catch when converting recursive tree algorithms to iterative ones?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You usually need an explicit data structure (like a stack) to keep track of work the recursion was managing automatically.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does recursion manage "for free" compared to iteration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Bookkeeping — the call stack stores per-call state, saving you from managing it by hand.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What data structure often replaces the call stack in an iterative version of a tree traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An explicit stack (e.g. an <code>ArrayList</code> or <code>Deque</code> used as a stack).</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If recursion and iteration are equivalent in power, why ever prefer recursion?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because for some problems, especially tree-structured ones, the recursive version is dramatically clearer and easier to reason about.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Stuff the College Board just had to get off their chest</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>System reliability is limited. Programmers should make an effort to maximize system reliability.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to say that "system reliability is limited"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No software system is perfectly reliable; failures and bugs are always possible.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What responsibility do programmers have regarding reliability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To make an effort to maximize the reliability of the systems they build.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name one programming practice that helps maximize reliability.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Writing and running tests to catch bugs before the software is deployed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't programmers guarantee 100% reliability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because software runs on imperfect hardware, handles unpredictable inputs, and is written by humans who make mistakes.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does error handling contribute to reliability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets a program recover or fail gracefully instead of crashing when unexpected conditions occur.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Legal issues and intellectual property concerns arise when creating programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of non-technical concerns arise from writing programs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Legal issues and intellectual property concerns.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an intellectual property concern for programmers.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Respecting software licenses when using third-party libraries.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a legal issue that can arise from a program.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Handling user data in compliance with privacy laws.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why should programmers care about licenses on open-source code they use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because licenses impose conditions on how the code may be used, modified, and redistributed.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Who owns the copyright on code a programmer writes at their job, usually?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Typically their employer, depending on the employment contract and jurisdiction.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The creation of programs has impacts on society, economies, and culture. These impacts can be beneficial and/or harmful.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name three domains the creation of programs can impact.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Society, economies, and culture.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are the impacts of software always positive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — they can be beneficial, harmful, or both at the same time.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a beneficial societal impact of software.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Medical software that helps doctors diagnose illnesses more accurately.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a harmful economic impact of software.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Automation displacing workers in certain industries.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do programmers have to think beyond the technical correctness of their code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because their work has real-world impacts on people, and those impacts deserve consideration.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When using the computer, personal privacy is at risk. Programmers should attempt to safeguard personal privacy.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What risk does using a computer pose to its user?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Their personal privacy can be compromised.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What responsibility do programmers have regarding user privacy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To attempt to safeguard personal privacy in the systems they build.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name one concrete way a programmer can protect user privacy.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Storing only the minimum personal data needed and encrypting sensitive fields.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is privacy especially at risk in networked software?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because data can be transmitted and aggregated across many systems, widening exposure.</p></answer>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does good authentication help safeguard privacy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By ensuring only authorized users can access personal information.</p></answer>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</content>
</invoke>
</deck>
